/title-21/section-21-1161.1 \u00a7 21-1161]\n|-\n| [[Oregon]]\n| Felony\n| [http://www.oregonlaws.org/ors/166.085 ORS \u00a7 166.085]\n|-\n| [[Pennsylvania]]\n| Misdemeanor (second degree)\n| [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.055.010.000..HTM 18 Pa. Cons. Stat. \u00a7 5510]\n|-\n| [[Rhode Island]]\n| Felony\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/rhode-island/2012/title-11/chapter-11-20/chapter-11-20-1.2 \u00a7 11-20-1.2]\n|-\n|[[South Carolina]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|[[South Dakota]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n| [[Tennessee]]\n| Felony (Class E)\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/tennessee/2010/title-39/chapter-17/part-3/39-17-312 \u00a7 39-17-312]\n|-\n| [[Texas]]\n| Misdemeanor (Class A)\n| [http://www.statutes.legis.state.tx.us/Docs/PE/htm/PE.42.htm#42.08 \u00a7 9.42.08]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statutes.legis.state.tx.us/Docs/PE/htm/PE.42.htm#42.08 |title=Texas Penal Code Chapter 42. Disorderly Conduct And Related Offenses |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428190550/http://www.statutes.legis.state.tx.us/Docs/PE/htm/PE.42.htm#42.08|archivedate=28 April 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Utah]]\n| Felony (third degree)\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/utah/2006/title76/76_0b041.html \u00a7 76-9-704]\n|-\n|[[Vermont]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|[[Virginia]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n| [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]]\n| Felony (Class C)\n| [http://apps.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=9A.44.105 RCW \u00a7 9A.44.105]\n|-\n|[[West Virginia]]\n|Misdemeanor\n|[http://www.wvlegislature.gov/wvcode/ChapterEntire.cfm?chap=61&art=8&section=9 \u00a7 61-8-9]\n|-\n| [[Wisconsin]]\n| Felony (Class G)\n| [http://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/statutes/statutes/940/II/225 \u00a7 940.225 (7)]<ref>Although the wording is somewhat ambiguous, the Supreme Court of Wisconsin determined this statute applied to \"sexual contact or sexual intercourse with a victim already dead at the time of the sexual activity when the accused did not cause the death of the victim\" in [http://www.wicourts.gov/sc/opinion/DisplayDocument.html?content=html&seqNo=33332 State v. Grunke].</ref>\n|-\n|[[Wyoming]]\n|Felony\n|[https://law.justia.com/codes/wyoming/2014/title-6/chapter-4/article-5/section-6-4-502/ \u00a7 6-4-502]\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [[Incidents of necrophilia]]\n* [[Necrophilia in popular culture]]\n* [[Vulnerability and care theory of love]]\n* [[Death during consensual sex]]\n* [[Karen Greenlee]]\n* [[Sir Jimmy Savile]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book | first=Anil |last= Aggrawal| date = 2010 | title = Necrophilia: Forensic and Medico-legal Aspects | publisher = CRC Press |location=Boca Raton, Florida| isbn= 978-1420089127|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Aggrawal|first=Anil|title=Necrophilia: Forensic and Medico-legal Aspects|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b0k2qpfyU8IC|date=19 April 2016|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4200-8913-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Finbow|first=Steve|title=Grave Desire: A Cultural History of Necrophilia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rGIpBQAAQBAJ|date=2014|publisher=Winchester, UK: Zero Books|isbn=978-1-7827-9342-7|ref=harv}}\n*Lee Mellor (2016) Homicide: A Forensic Psychology Casebook. CRC Press. {{ISBN|9781498731522}}.\n*{{cite book|last1=Purcell|first1=Catherine|last2=Arrigo|first2=Bruce A.|title=The Psychology of Lust Murder: Paraphilia, Sexual Killing, and Serial Homicide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=agmkfIgbQxUC|date=7 June 2006|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-08-046257-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=West|first1=Sarah G.|last2=Resnick|first2=Phillip J.|chapter=Necrophilia|title=Unusual and Rare Psychological Disorders: A Handbook for Clinical Practice and Research|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dgc1DQAAQBAJ|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-024586-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Lisa Downing]], ''Desiring the Dead: Necrophilia and Nineteenth-Century French Literature''. Oxford: Legenda, 2003\n*[[Richard von Krafft-Ebing]], ''Psychopathia Sexualis''. New York: Stein & Day, 1965. Originally published in 1886.\n\n=== In literature ===\n\n*[[Gabrielle Wittkop]], ''The Necrophiliac'', 1972\n*[[Barbara Gowdy]], ''We So Seldom Look on Love'', 1992\n*[[Frank O'Hara]], ''Ode on Necrophilia'', 1960\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB     =\n|  ICD10          = {{ICD10|F|65.8}} \n}}\n{{Paraphilia}}\n{{Death}}\n{{Human sexuality}}\n{{Sexual ethics}}\n{{Sex fetish}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Necrophilia| ]]\n[[Category:Paraphilias]]\n[[Category:Sex crimes]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy-edit|date=January 2020}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Necrophila]], a genus of beetles}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Necrophilia\n| synonyms        = \n| image           = Pietro Pajetta - Der Hass - 1896.jpg\n| caption         = ''The Hatred'', painted by [[Pietro Pajetta]], 1896.\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Psychiatry]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Necrophilia''', also known as '''necrophilism''', '''necrolagnia''', '''necrocoitus''', '''necrochlesis''', and '''thanatophilia''',{{sfn|Aggrawal|2016|p=1}} is [[sexual attraction]] towards or a sexual act involving [[Cadaver|corpses]]. It is classified as a [[paraphilia]] by the [[World Health Organisation]] (WHO) in the organisation's ''International Classification of Diseases'' ([[ICD10|ICD)]] diagnostic manual, as well as by the [[American Psychiatric Association]]<ref name=\"Goodwin\">{{cite book|editor1-first=Robin|editor1-last=Goodwin|editor2-first=Duncan|editor2-last=Cranmer|title=Inappropriate Relationships: The Unconventional, the Disapproved, and the Forbidden|pages=174\u2013176|publisher=Psychology Press|location=London, England|date=2002|isbn= 978-0805837421}}</ref> in its ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual]]'' (DSM).\n\n==Origins of term==\nThe term 'necrophilia' is thought to have been coined by Belgian physician [[Joseph Guislain]] in his ''Le\u00e7ons Orales sur les Phr\u00e9nopathies'' in a lecture given around 1850, about contemporary necrophiliac [[Fran\u00e7ois Bertrand]]:{{sfn|Aggrawal|2016|p=4}}\n\n{{quote|It is within the category of the destructive madmen [''ali\u00e9n\u00e9s destructeurs''] that one needs to situate certain patients to whom I would like to give the name of necrophiliacs [''n\u00e9crophiles'']. The alienists have adopted, as a new form, the case of Sergeant Bertrand, the disinterrer of cadavers on whom all the newspapers have recently reported. However, don't think that we are dealing here with a form of phrenopathy which appears for the first time. The ancients, in speaking about [[lycanthropy]], have cited examples to which one can more or less relate the case which has just now attracted the public attention so strongly.}}\nPsychiatrist [[B\u00e9n\u00e9dict Morel]] popularised the term about a decade later when discussing Bertrand.<ref name=\"Goodwin\" />\n\n==History==\nIn the ancient world, sailors returning corpses to their home country were often accused of necrophilia.{{sfn|Aggrawal|2016|p=2}} Singular accounts of necrophilia in history are sporadic, though written records suggest the practice was present within [[Ancient Egypt]]. [[Herodotus]] writes in [[Histories (Herodotus)|''The Histories'']] that, to discourage intercourse with a corpse, ancient [[Egypt]]ians left deceased beautiful women to decay for \"three or four days\" before giving them to the [[embalmers]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Herodotus (c. 440 BC) |title=The Histories (Book 2) |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/2707 |quote=The wives of men of rank when they die are not given at once to be embalmed, nor such women as are very beautiful or of greater regard than others, but on the third or fourth day after their death (and not before) they are delivered to the embalmers. They do so about this matter in order that the embalmers may not abuse their women, for they say that one of them was taken once doing so to the corpse of a woman lately dead, and his fellow-craftsman gave information.|date=July 2001 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Brill | first1 = Abraham A. | date= 1941 | title = Necrophilia | journal = Journal of Criminal Psychopathology | volume = 2 | issue = 4| pages = 433\u2013443 }}</ref><ref name=\"klaf\">{{cite journal |first1=Franklin S.|last1=Klaf |first2=William|last2=Brown  |date= 1958 | title = Necrophilia: Brief Review and Case Report | journal = Psychiatric Quarterly | volume = 32 | issue = 4 | pages = 645\u2013652 | quote = Inhibited forms of necrophilia and necrophiliac fantasies may occur more commonly then is generally realised. | doi=10.1007/bf01563024|pmid=13634264 }}</ref> Herodotus also alluded to suggestions that Greek tyrant [[Periander]] had defiled the corpse of his wife, employing a metaphor: \"Periander baked his bread in a cold oven.\"{{sfn|Aggrawal|2010|pp=6\u20137, The primary source is ''Histories'', Book V, 92}} Acts of necrophilia are depicted on ceramics from the [[Moche (culture)|Moche]] culture, which reigned in northern [[Peru]] from the first to eighth century CE.<ref>{{cite book |first=Steve|last=Finbow | date = 2014 | title = Grave Desire: A Cultural History of Necrophilia | publisher = John Hunt Publishing | url = https://books.google.com/?id=rGIpBQAAQBAJ&lpg=PT4&pg=PT39|isbn=9781782793410 }}</ref> A common theme in these artifacts is the masturbation of a male skeleton by a living woman.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Weismantel, M. | year = 2004 | title = Moche sex pots: Reproduction and temporality in ancient South America | journal = American Anthropologist | volume = 106 | issue = 3 | pages = 495\u2013496 | url = http://www.latinamericanstudies.org/moche/moche-sex-pots.pdf | doi=10.1525/aa.2004.106.3.495}}</ref> [[Hittites|Hittite]] law from the 16th century BC through to the 13th century BC explicitly permitted sex with the dead.<ref>{{cite book | author = Boer, Roland | year = 2014 | title = Sex in Antiquity: Exploring Gender and Sexuality in the Ancient World | chapter = From Horse Kissing to Beastly Emissions: Paraphilias in the Ancient Near East | editor = Masterson, Mark | publisher = Routledge | page = 69 | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=k1G2BQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA69&ots=DtUbHRO19Dlr&pg=PA69#v=onepage}}</ref> In what is now [[Northeast China]], the ethnic [[Xianbei]] emperor [[Murong Xi]] (385\u2013407) of the [[Later Yan]] state had intercourse with the corpse of his beloved empress [[Fu Xunying]], after the latter was already cold and put into the coffin.<ref>{{cite book|title=Tales about Chinese Emperors: Their Wild and Wise Ways|chapter=The Corpse-Raping Emperor|last=Luan Pao-ch\u00fcn|year=1994|pages=148\u2013?|publisher=Hai Feng Publishing Company}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Renaissance Italy]], following the reputed moral collapse brought about by the [[Black Death]] and before the [[Roman Inquisition]] of the [[Counter-Reformation]], literature was replete with sexual references; these include necrophilia, as in the epic poem ''[[Orlando Innamorato]]'' by [[Matteo Maria Boiardo]], first published in 1483.<ref name=\"DavidsonDean1994\">{{cite book|last1=Davidson|first1=Nicholas|title=Crime, Society and the Law in Renaissance Italy|last2=Dean|first2=Trevor|last3=Lowe|first3=K. J. P.|year=1994|pages=74\u201398|doi=10.1017/CBO9780511523410.006|isbn=9780511523410}}</ref> In a notorious modern example, American [[serial killer]] [[Jeffrey Dahmer]] was a necrophiliac. Dahmer wanted to create a [[sex slave]] that would mindlessly consent to whatever he wanted. When his attempts failed, and his male victim died, he would keep the corpse until it decomposed beyond recognition, continuously masturbating and performing sexual intercourse on the body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.comicextra.com/my-friend-dahmer/chapter-Full/214|title=My Friend Dahmer #Full \u2013 Read My Friend Dahmer Issue #Full Page 214|website=www.comicextra.com|access-date=20 December 2017}}</ref> To be aroused, he had to murder his male victims before performing sexual intercourse with them. Dahmer stated that he only killed his victims because they wanted to leave after having sex, and would be angry with him for drugging them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Psychiatric Testimony of Jeffrey Dahmer|url=http://www.criminalprofiling.com/Psychiatric-Testimony-of-Jeffrey-Dahmer_s115.html|work=Court Transcripts|publisher=Criminal Profiling|date=8 June 2001|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> British serial killer [[Dennis Nilsen]] is also considered to have been a necrophiliac.<ref>{{cite book | author = Masters, Brian | year = 1985 | title = Killing For Company | publisher = Arrow | isbn = 978-0099552611}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\nIn the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]], fifth edition ([[DSM-5]]), recurrent, intense sexual interest in corpses can be diagnosed under [[Other Specified Paraphilic Disorder]] (necrophilia) when it causes marked distress or impairment in important areas of functioning.<ref name=\"DSM-5\">{{cite book | title = Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition | chapter = Other Specified Paraphilic Disorder, 302.89 (F65.89) | editor = American Psychiatric Association | year = 2013 | publisher = American Psychiatric Publishing | page = 705}}</ref> A ten-tier classification of necrophilia exists:<ref name=\"aggrawal_classification\">{{cite journal |author=Aggrawal, Anil |title=A new classification of necrophilia |journal=Journal of Forensic and Legal Medicine |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=316\u201320 |year=2009 |pmid=19573840 |doi=10.1016/j.jflm.2008.12.023 }} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n# Role players: People who get aroused when [[Sexual roleplay|pretending]] their partner is dead during sexual activity.\n# Romantic necrophiliacs: Bereaved people who remain attached to their dead lover's body.\n# Necrophiliac fantasisers: People who fantasise about necrophilia, but never actually have sex with a corpse.\n# Tactile necrophiliacs: People who are aroused by touching or stroking a corpse, without engaging in intercourse.\n# [[Sexual fetishism|Fetishistic]] necrophiliacs: People who remove objects (e.g., panties or a tampon) or body parts (e.g., a finger or genitalia) from a corpse for sexual purposes, without engaging in intercourse.\n# Necromutilomaniacs: People who derive pleasure from mutilating a corpse while masturbating, without engaging in intercourse.\n# Opportunistic necrophiliacs: People who normally have no interest in necrophilia, but take the opportunity when it arises.\n# Regular necrophiliacs: People who preferentially have intercourse with the dead.\n# Homicidal necrophiliacs: Necrosadists,{{sfn|Purcell|Arrigo|2006|p=21}} people who [[lust murder|murder]] someone in order to have sex with the victim.\n# Exclusive necrophiliacs: People who have an exclusive interest in sex with the dead, and cannot perform at all for a living partner.\nAdditionally, criminologist [[Lee Mellor]]'s typology of homicidal necrophiliacs consists of eight categories (A\u2013H), and is based on the combination of two behavioural axes: destructive (offender [[Mutilation|mutilates]] the corpse for sexual reasons) \u2013 preservative (offender does not), and cold (offender used the corpse sexually two hours after death) \u2013 warm (offender used the corpse sexually earlier than two hours after death).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Homicide: A Forensic Psychology Casebook|last=Mellor|first=Lee|publisher=CRC|year=2016|location=Boca Raton, FL|pages=103\u2013105}}</ref> This renders four categories (A-D) to which Mellor adds an additional four (E-H):\n* Category A (cold/destructive), e.g. [[Ted Bundy]], [[Jeffrey Dahmer]]\n* Category B (cold/preservative), e.g. [[Gary Ridgway]], [[Dennis Nilsen]]\n* Category C (warm/destructive) e.g. [[Andrei Chikatilo]], [[Joseph Vacher]]\n* Category D (warm/preservative) e.g. [[Robert Lee Yates|Robert Yates]], [[Earle Nelson]]\n* Category E (dabblers) e.g. [[Richard Ramirez]], [[Mark Dixie]]\n* Category F (catathymic\u2060\u2009\u2060\u2014\u2009impulsively and explosively lashing out) \n* Category G (exclusive necromutilophiles) e.g. [[Robert Napper]], [[Peter Sutcliffe]]\n* Category H (sexual [[Human cannibalism|cannibals]] & vampires) e.g. [[Albert Fish]], [[Peter K\u00fcrten]]<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nDabblers have transitory opportunistic sexual relations with corpses, but this is not their preference. Category F homicidal necrophiliacs commit postmortem sex acts only while in a catathymic state. Exclusive mutilophiles derive pleasure purely from mutilating the corpse, while sexual [[Human cannibalism|cannibals]] and vampires are sexually aroused by eating human body parts. Category A, C, and F offenders may also cannibalise or drink the blood of their victims.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Research==\n\n===Humans===\nNecrophilia is often assumed to be rare, but no data for its prevalence in the general population exists.<ref>{{cite book | author =  Milner, J. S., Dopke, C. A., & Crouch, J. L.  | date= 2008 | title = Sexual Deviance: Theory, Assessment, and Treatment, 2nd edition | publisher = The Guilford Press | page = 399 | chapter = Paraphilia Not Otherwise Specified: Psychopathology and Theory | editor = Laws, D. Richard}}</ref> Some necrophiliacs only fantasise about the act, without carrying it out.<ref name=\"rosman\" /> In 1958, Klaf and Brown commented that, although rarely described, necrophiliac [[fantasy (psychology)|fantasies]] may occur more often than is generally supposed.<ref name=\"klaf\"/>\n\nRosman and Resnick (1989) reviewed 122 cases of necrophilia. The sample was divided into genuine necrophiliacs, who had a persistent attraction to corpses, and pseudo-necrophiliacs, who acted out of opportunity, sadism, or transient interest.  Of the total, 92% were male and 8% were female. 57% of the genuine necrophiliacs had occupational access to corpses, with morgue attendants, hospital orderly, and cemetery employees being the most common jobs. The researchers theorised that either of the following situations could be antecedents to necrophilia:<ref name=\"rosman\" />\n#The necrophiliac develops poor [[self-esteem]], perhaps due in part to a significant loss;\n#:(a) They are very fearful of rejection by others and they desire a sexual partner who is incapable of rejecting them; and/or\n#:(b) They are fearful of the dead, and transform their fear\u2014by means of [[reaction formation]]\u2014into a desire.\n#They develop an exciting fantasy of sex with a corpse, sometimes after exposure to a corpse.\n\n====Motives====\nThe most common motive for necrophiliacs is the possession of a partner who is unresisting or unrejecting. However, in the past, necrophiliacs have expressed having more than one motive.<ref name=\"Resnick 412\u2013417\">{{Cite journal|last=Resnick|first=Phillip J.|last2=Soliman|first2=Sherif|date=September 2012|title=Planning, writing, and editing forensic psychiatric reports|journal=International Journal of Law and Psychiatry|volume=35|issue=5\u20136|pages=412\u2013417|doi=10.1016/j.ijlp.2012.09.019|pmid=23040708|issn=0160-2527}}</ref>\n\nThe authors reported that of their sample of genuine necrophiliacs:<ref name=\"rosman\" />\n*68% were motivated by a desire for a non-resisting and non-rejecting partner;\n*21% by a want for a reunion with a lost partner;\n*15% by sexual attraction to dead people;\n*15% by a desire for comfort or to overcome feelings of isolation\n*12% by a desire to remedy low self-esteem by expressing power over a corpse.\n\nLesser common motives include:\n\n* Unavailability of a living partner\n* Compensation for a fear of women\n* Belief that sex with a living woman was a mortal sin\n* Need to achieve a feeling of total control over a sexual partner\n* Compliance with a command hallucination\n* Performance of a series of destructive acts\n* Expression of polymorphous perverse sexual desires\n* Need to perform limitless sexual activity<ref name=\"Resnick 412\u2013417\"/>\n\nIQ data was limited, but not abnormally low. About half of the sample had a personality disorder, and 11% of true necrophiliacs were psychotic. Rosman and Resnick concluded that their data challenged the conventional view of necrophiliacs as generally psychotic, mentally deficient, or unable to obtain a consenting partner.<ref name=\"rosman\" />\n\nRosman and Resnick (1989) reviewed information from 34 cases of necrophilia describing the individuals' motivations for their behaviours. These individuals reported the desire to possess a non-resisting and non-rejecting partner (68%), reunions with a deceased romantic partner (21%), sexual attraction to corpses (15%), overcoming feelings of isolation (15%), and seeking self-esteem by expressing power over a homicide victim (12%).<ref name=\"rosman\">{{cite journal | last1 = Rosman | first1 = J. P. | last2 = Resnick | first2 = P. J. | date = 1 June 1989 | title = Sexual attraction to corpses: A psychiatric review of necrophilia | url = http://www.jaapl.org/content/17/2/153.full.pdf+html?sid=94a1e953-67b0-44c0-95a6-75ee304d916e | format=PDF/HTML| journal = Bulletin of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law |volume = 17 | issue = 2| pages = 153\u2013163 | pmid = 2667656 }}</ref>\n\n===Other animals===\n[[File:Salvator merianae - necrophilia.jpg|thumb|290px|A male [[Argentine black and white tegu|black and white tegu]] mounts a female that has been dead for two days and attempts to mate.<ref name=\"sazima\" />]]\n{{see also|Non-reproductive sexual behaviour in animals}}\n\nNecrophilia has been observed in mammals, birds, reptiles and frogs.<ref name=\"demattos\">{{cite journal | author = de Mattos Brito, L. B., Joventino, I. R., Ribeiro, S. C., & Cascon, P. | year = 2012 | title = Necrophiliac behaviour in the \"cururu\" toad, ''Rhinella jimi'' Steuvax, 2002, (Anura, Bufonidae) from Northeastern Brazil | journal = North-Western Journal of Zoology | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | page = 365 | url = http://biozoojournals.ro/nwjz/content/v8n2/nwjz.121206.Brito.pdf}}</ref> In 1960, Robert Dickerman described necrophilia in [[ground squirrel]]s, which he termed \"Davian behaviour\" in reference to a [[limerick (poetry)|limerick]] about a necrophiliac miner named Dave. The label is still used for necrophilia in animals.<ref name=\"costa\" /> Certain species of arachnids and insects practice [[sexual cannibalism]], in which the female cannibalises her male mate before, during, or after copulation.\n\n[[Kees Moeliker]] made one observation while he was sitting in his office at the [[Natural History Museum Rotterdam]], when he heard the distinctive thud of a bird hitting the glass facade of the building. Upon inspection, he discovered a drake (male) [[mallard]] lying dead outside the building. Next to the downed bird, a second drake mallard was standing close by. As Moeliker observed the couple, the living drake pecked at the corpse of the dead one for a few minutes then mounted the corpse and began copulating with it. The act of necrophilia lasted for about 75 minutes, in which time, according to Moeliker, the living drake took two short breaks before resuming with copulating behaviour. Moeliker surmised that at the time of the collision with the window the two mallards were engaged in a common pattern in [[duck]] behaviour called \"attempted [[rape]] flight\". \"When one died the other one just went for it and didn't get any negative feedback \u2013 well, didn't get any feedback,\" according to Moeliker.<ref name=\"Mallard Duck\">{{cite journal | author=C.W. Moeliker| title=The first case of homosexual necrophilia in the Anas platyrhynchos (Aves:Anatidae)| journal=Deinsea \u2013 Annual of the Natural History Museum Rotterdam| year=2001| volume=8| pages=243\u2013247 |url=http://www.chm.bris.ac.uk/sillymolecules/papers/duck.pdf |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MallardDuck\">{{cite news | url=http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/research/story/0,9865,1432991,00.html | title = Necrophilia among ducks ruffles research feathers|accessdate = 17 June 2007|publisher=Guardian Unlimited|author=Donald MacLeod | location=London | date=8 March 2005| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207231131/http://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/mar/08/highereducation.research| archivedate=7 December 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Necrophilia had previously only been reported in heterosexual mallard pairs.<ref name=\"Mallard Duck\" />\n\nIn a short paper known as \"Sexual Habits of the Ad\u00e9lie Penguin\", deemed too shocking for contemporary publication, [[George Murray Levick]] described \"little hooligan bands\" of penguins mating with dead females in the [[Cape Adare]] [[rookery]], the largest group of [[Ad\u00e9lie penguin]]s, in 1911 and 1912.<ref>{{cite news|last=McKie|first=Robin|title='Sexual depravity' of penguins that Antarctic scientist dared not reveal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/09/sex-depravity-penguins-scott-antarctic|accessdate=9 June 2012|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=9 June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005160644/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/09/sex-depravity-penguins-scott-antarctic|archivedate=5 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"russel\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Russell | first1 = D. G. D. | last2 = Sladen | first2 = W. J. L. | last3 = Ainley | first3 = D. G. | title = Dr. George Murray Levick (1876\u20131956): Unpublished notes on the sexual habits of the Ad\u00e9lie penguin | doi = 10.1017/S0032247412000216 | journal = Polar Record | volume = 48 | issue = 4 | pages = 1 | year = 2012 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/425cc23d80076c2dd6f289b77bfb3b39471dc9b1 }}</ref> This is nowadays ascribed to lack of experience of young penguins; a dead female, with eyes half-closed, closely resembles a compliant female.<ref name=\"GD2012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/09/sex-depravity-penguins-scott-antarctic |title='Sexual depravity' of penguins that Antarctic scientist dared not reveal |newspaper=Guardian.co.uk |date=9 June 2012 |first=Robin |last=McKie |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104114948/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/09/sex-depravity-penguins-scott-antarctic |archivedate=4 November 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> A [[gentoo penguin]] was observed attempting to have intercourse with a dead penguin in 1921.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Bagshawe, T. W. | year = 1938 | title = Notes on the Habits of the Gentoo and Ringed or Antarctic Penguins | journal = The Transactions of the Zoological Society of London | volume = 24 | issue = 3 | page = 209 | doi=10.1111/j.1096-3642.1938.tb00391.x}}</ref>\n\nA male [[New Zealand sea lion]] was once observed attempting to copulate with a dead female [[New Zealand fur seal]] in the wild. The sea lion nudged the seal repeatedly, then mounted her and made several pelvic thrusts. Approximately ten minutes later, the sea lion became disturbed by the researcher's presence, dragged the corpse of the seal into the water and swam away while holding it.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Wilson, G. J. | year = 1979 | title = Hooker's sea lions in southern New Zealand | journal = New Zealand Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 373\u2013375 | doi=10.1080/00288330.1979.9515812}}</ref> A male [[sea otter]] was observed holding a female sea otter underwater until she drowned, and then repeatedly copulating with her carcass. Several months later, the same sea otter was again observed copulating with the carcass of a different female.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Harris, H. S., Oates, S. C., Staedler, M. M., Tinker, M. T., Jessup, D. A., Harvey, J. T., & Miller, M. A. | year = 2010 | title = Lesions and behaviour associated with forced copulation of juvenile Pacific harbor seals (''Phoca vitulina richardsi'') by southern sea otters (''Enhydra lutris nereis'') | journal = Aquatic Mammals | volume = 36 | issue = 4 | page = 338 | url = http://werc.ucsc.edu/Publications/2010%20Harris%20et%20al.pdf | doi=10.1578/am.36.4.2010.331}}</ref> Copulation with a dead female [[pilot whale]] by a captive male pilot whale has been observed,<ref>{{cite journal | author = Brown, D. H. | year = 1962 | title = Further observations on the pilot whale in captivity | journal = Zoologica | volume = 47 | issue = 1 | pages = 59\u201364}}</ref> and possible sexual behaviour between two male [[humpback whale]]s, one dead, has also been reported.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Pack, A. A., Salden, D. R., Ferrari, M. J., Glockner\u2010Ferrari, D. A., Herman, L. M., Stubbs, H. A., & Straley, J. M. | year = 1998 | title = Male humpback whale dies in competitive group | journal = Marine Mammal Science | volume = 14 | issue = 4 | pages = 861\u2013873 | doi=10.1111/j.1748-7692.1998.tb00771.x}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, a male [[rock dove]] was observed copulating with the corpse of a dove that had shortly before had its head crushed by a car.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Slavid, Evelyn |author2=Taylor, Julie | year = 1987 | title = Feral Rock Dove displaying to and attempting to copulate with corpse of another | journal = British Birds | volume = 8 | issue = 10 | page = 497 | url = http://www.britishbirds.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/article_files/V80/V80_N10/V80_N10_P492_502_N115.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian 2: Electric Boogaloo\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/mar/14/research.highereducation | title = Randy rock doves join party with the dead | accessdate = 17 June 2007 | work = [[The Guardian]] | location=London | date=14 March 2005}}</ref> In 2001, a researcher laid out [[sand martin]] corpses to attract flocks of other sand martins. In each of six trials, 1\u20135 individuals from flocks of 50\u2013500 were observed attempting to copulate with the dead sand martins. This occurred one to two months after the breeding season; since copulation outside the breeding season is uncommon among birds, the researcher speculated that the lack of resistance by the corpses stimulated the behaviour.<ref name=\"dale\">{{cite journal | author = Dale, S. | year = 2001 | title = Necrophilic behaviour, corpses as nuclei of resting flock formation, and road-kills of Sand Martins ''Riparia riparia'' | journal = Ardea | volume = 89 | issue = 3 | pages = 545\u2013547 | url = http://www.avibirds.com/pdf/O/Oeverzwaluw3.pdf}}</ref> Charles Brown observed at least ten [[cliff swallow]]s attempt to copulate with a road-killed cliff swallow in the space of 15 minutes. He commented, \"This isn't the first time I've seen cliff swallows do this; the bright orange rump sticking up seems to be all the stimulus these birds need.\"<ref>{{cite book | author = Charles Robert Brown | year = 1998 | title = Swallow Summer | url = https://archive.org/details/swallowsummer00brow | url-access = registration | publisher = University of Nebraska Press | page = [https://archive.org/details/swallowsummer00brow/page/143 143]}}</ref> Necrophilia has also been reported in the [[European swallow]], [[grey-backed sparrow-lark]], [[Stark's lark]],<ref name=\"russel\" /> and the [[snow goose]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = McKinney, F., & Evarts, S. | year = 1998 | title = Sexual coercion in waterfowl and other birds | journal = Ornithological Monographs | issue = 49 | pages = 163\u2013195 | doi = 10.2307/40166723| jstor = 40166723 }} The primary source ([https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v093n03/p0701-p0711.pdf Gauthier & Tardif, 1991]) states that \"a paired male attempted to mount a recently shot bird used to attract other geese.\"</ref> A Norwegian television report showed a male [[hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] between a [[black grouse]] and [[western capercaillie]] kill a male black grouse before attempting to copulate with it.<ref name=\"dale\" /> In 2015, due to work done by the [[University of Washington]], it was found that [[crows]] would commit necrophilia on dead crow corpses in about 4% of encounters with corpses.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Yong |first=Ed |date=18 July 2018 |title=Crows Sometimes Have Sex With Their Dead |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/crow-necrophilia/565442/ |magazine= The Atlantic |access-date=26 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ameiva ameiva - necrophilia.jpg|thumb|290px|A male ''[[Ameiva ameiva]]'' mounts a dead female and attempts to pair cloacae.<ref name=\"costa\" />]]\n\nNecrophilia has been documented in various lizard species, including  ''[[Ameiva ameiva]]'',<ref name=\"costa\">{{cite journal | author = Costa, H. C., da Silva, E. T., Campos, P. S., da Cunha Oliveira, M. P., Nunes, A. V., & da Silva Santos, P. | year = 2010 | title = The corpse bride: a case of Davian behaviour in the green ameiva (''Ameiva ameiva'') in southeastern Brazil | journal = Herpetology Notes | volume = 3 | pages = 79\u201383 | url = http://herpetologynotes.seh-herpetology.org/Volume3_PDFs/Costa_et_al_Herpetology_Notes_Volume3_pages079-083.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author = Vitt, L.J. | year = 2003 | chapter = Life versus sex: the ultimate choice | title = Lizards: Windows to the Evolution of Diversity | chapter-url = https://archive.org/details/lizardswindowsto00pian | chapter-url-access = registration | page = [https://archive.org/details/lizardswindowsto00pian/page/103 103] | publisher = University of California Press}}</ref> the [[leopard lizard]],<ref>{{cite journal | author = Fallahpour, K. | year = 2005 | title = ''Gambelia wislizenii''. Necrophilia. | journal = Herpetological Review | volume = 36 | pages = 177\u2013178}} Cited in Sazima (2015).</ref> and ''[[Holbrookia maculata]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Brinker, A.M, Bucklin, S.E. | year = 2006 | title = ''Holbrookia maculata''. Necrophilia. | journal = Herpetological Review | volume = 37 | page = 466}} Cited in Sazima (2015).</ref> There are two reports of necrophilic behaviour in the sleepy lizard (''[[Tiliqua rugosa]]''). In one, the partner of a male lizard got caught in fencing wire and died. The male continued to display courtship behaviour towards his partner two days after her death. This lizard's necrophilia was believed to stem from its strong [[Monogamous pairing in animals|monogamous]] bond.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Bull, C. Michael | title = Monogamy in lizards | journal = Behavioural Processes | volume = 51 | issue = 1 | page = 12 | url = http://aerg.canberra.edu.au/library/sex_reptile/2000_Bull_monogamy_in_lizards.pdf | doi=10.1016/s0376-6357(00)00115-7| year = 2000 }}</ref> In one study of [[Argentine black and white tegu|black and white tegu]] lizards, two different males were observed attempting to court and copulate with a single female corpse on two consecutive days. On the first day, the corpse was freshly dead, but by the second day it was bloating and emitting a strong putrefying odor. The researcher attributed the behaviour to [[sex pheromone]]s still acting on the carcass.<ref name=\"sazima\">{{cite journal | author = Sazima, I. | year = 2015 | title = Corpse bride irresistible: a dead female tegu lizard (''Salvator merianae'') courted by males for two days at an urban park in South-eastern Brazil | journal = Herpetology Notes | volume = 8 | pages = 15\u201318 | url = http://www.biotaxa.org/hn/article/download/9131/11610}}</ref>\n\nMale [[garter snake]]s often copulate with dead females.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Shine, R., O'Connor, D., & Mason, R. T. | year = 2000 | title = Sexual conflict in the snake den | journal = Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology | volume = 48 | issue = 5 | page = 397 | url = http://masonlab.science.oregonstate.edu/files/masonlab/055sexualconflict.pdf | doi = 10.1007/s002650000255 | access-date = 25 February 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100620133426/http://masonlab.science.oregonstate.edu/files/masonlab/055sexualconflict.pdf | archive-date = 20 June 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Joy, J. E., & Crews, D. | year = 1985 | title = Social dynamics of group courtship behavior in male red-sided garter snakes (''Thamnophis sirtalis parietalis'') | journal = Journal of Comparative Psychology | volume = 99 | issue = 2 | page = 148 | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/19156376 | doi=10.1037/0735-7036.99.2.145}}</ref> One case has been reported in the ''[[Bothrops jararaca]]'' snake with a dead [[South American rattlesnake]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Amaral. A. | year = 1932 | title = Contribui\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e0 biologia dos ophidios do Brasil. IV. Sobre um caso de necrophilia heterologa na jararaca (''Bothrops jararaca'') | journal = Mem\u00f3rias do Instituto de Butantan | volume = 7 | pages = 93\u201394}} Cited in Costa et al. (2010).</ref><ref name=\"klauber718\">{{cite book | author = Klauber, Laurence Monroe | year = 1972 | title = Rattlesnakes: Their Habits, Life Histories, and Influence on Mankind, Volume 1 | publisher = University of California Press | page = 718 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ijblNZQrk_wC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA718#v=onepage| isbn = 9780520017757 }}</ref> The prairie rattlesnake (''[[Crotalus viridis]]'') and ''[[Helicops carinicaudus]]'' snake have both been seen attempting to mate with decapitated females, presumably attracted by still-active [[sex pheromone]]s.<ref name=\"klauber718\" /><ref>{{cite journal | author = Santos, S. M. A., Siqueira, R., Coeti, R. Z., Cavalheri, D., & Trevine, V. | year = 2015 | title = The sexual attractiveness of the corpse bride: unusual mating behaviour of Helicops carinicaudus (Serpentes: Dipsadidae) | journal = Herpetology Notes | volume = 8 | pages = 643\u2013647 | url = http://www.biotaxa.org/hn/article/view/14442}}</ref> Male [[crayfish]] sometimes copulate with dead crayfish of either sex, and in one observation even with a dead crayfish of a different species.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Pearse, A. S. | year = 1909 | title = Observations on copulation among crawfishes with special reference to sex recognition | journal = American Naturalist | page = 752 | doi=10.1086/279107 | volume=43| issue = 516 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Andrews, E. A. | year = 1910 | title = Conjugation in the crayfish, ''Cambarus affinis'' | journal = Journal of Experimental Zoology | volume = 9 | issue = 2 | pages = 235\u2013264 | doi=10.1002/jez.1400090202| url = https://zenodo.org/record/1426855 }}</ref>\n\nIn frogs, it has been observed in the [[foothill yellow-legged frog]],<ref>{{cite journal | author = Bettaso, J., Haggarthy, A., Russel, E. | year = 2008 | title = ''Rana boylii'' (Foothill Yellow-legged Frog). Necrogamy. | journal = Herpetological Review | volume = 39 | page = 462}} Cited in Costa et al. (2010).</ref> the yellow [[fire-bellied toad]],<ref>{{cite journal | author = Sinovas, P. | year = 2009 | title = ''Bombina variegata'' (Yellow Fire-bellied Toad). Mating Behaviour | journal = Herpetological Review | volume = 40 | page = 199}} Cited in Costa et al. (2010).</ref> the [[common frog]],<ref name=\"mollov\">{{cite journal | author = Mollov, I. A., Popgeorgiev, G. S., Naumov, B. Y., Tzankov, N. D., & Stoyanov, A. Y. | year = 2010 | title = Cases of abnormal amplexus in anurans (Amphibia: Anura) from Bulgaria and Greece. | journal = Biharean Biologist | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages = 121\u2013125 | url = http://web.uni-plovdiv.bg/mollov/pdf/Mollov_et_al_%282010%29.pdf}}</ref> the [[Oregon spotted frog]],<ref>{{cite journal | author = Pearl, C. A., Hayes, M. P., Haycock, R., Engler, J. D., & Bowerman, J. | year = 2005 | title = Observations of interspecific amplexus between western North American ranid frogs and the introduced American bullfrog (''Rana catesbeiana'') and an hypothesis concerning breeding interference | journal = The American Midland Naturalist | volume = 154 | issue = 1 | pages = 126\u2013134 | doi=10.1674/0003-0031(2005)154[0126:ooiabw]2.0.co;2}}</ref> ''[[Dendropsophus columbianus]]'',<ref>{{cite journal | author = Bedoya, S. C., Mantilla-Casta\u00f1o, J. C., & Pareja-M\u00e1rquez, I. M. | year = 2014 | title = Necrophiliac and interspecific amplexus in ''Dendropsophus columbianus'' (Anura: Hylidae) in the Central Cordillera of Colombia | journal = Herpetology Notes | volume = 7 | pages = 515\u2013516 | url = http://www.herpetologynotes.seh-herpetology.org/Volume7_PDFs/Bedoya_HerpetologyNotes_volume7_pp515-516.pdf}}</ref> and ''[[Rhinella jimi]]''.<ref name=\"demattos\" /> The film ''[[Cane Toads: An Unnatural History]]'' shows a male toad copulating with a female toad that had been run over by a car. It goes on to do this for eight hours.<ref>{{cite book | author = Lewis, Stephanie | year = 1989 | title = Cane Toads: an Unnatural History | url = https://archive.org/details/canetoadsunnatur0000lewi | url-access = registration | publisher = Doubleday | location = New York}}</ref> Necrophilic [[amplexus]] in frogs may occur because males will mount any pliable object the size of an adult female. If the mounted object is a live frog not appropriate for mating, it will vibrate its body or vocalise a call to be released. Dead frogs cannot do this, so they may be held for hours.<ref name=\"mollov\" /> The Amazonian frog ''[[Rhinella proboscidea]]'' sometimes practices what has been termed \"functional necrophilia\": a male grasps the corpse of a dead female and squeezes it until [[oocyte]]s are ejected, and then fertilises them.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Izzo, T. J., Rodrigues, D. J., Menin, M., Lima, A. P., & Magnusson, W. E. | year = 2012 | title = Functional necrophilia: a profitable anuran reproductive strategy? | journal = Journal of Natural History | volume = 46 | issue = 47\u201348 | pages = 2961\u20132967 | doi=10.1080/00222933.2012.724720}}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\nTreatment for Necrophilia is similar to that prescribed for most [[paraphilia]]s. Besides advocating treatment of the associated [[psychopathology]], there is little known on the treatment of Necrophilia. There has not been a sufficient number of necrophiliacs to establish any effective treatments. However, based on the available data, clinicians are suggested to:\n\n* Determine whether or not a person has Necrophilia\n* Treat any psychopathology that is associated with Necrophilia\n* Establish psycho-therapeutic rapport\n* If the person is male and has a heightened sex drive, provide him with anti-androgens\n* If the person is sexually isolated, help him find a normal sexual relationship\n* Desensitisation to help divert the necrophilic fantasies to a living object<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lazarus|first=Arnold A.|date=January 1968|title=A case of pseudo-necrophilia treated by behaviour therapy|journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology|volume=24|issue=1|pages=113\u2013115|doi=10.1002/1097-4679(196801)24:1<113::aid-jclp2270240137>3.0.co;2-q|issn=0021-9762}}</ref>\n\n== Case studies ==\n\n=== Jeffrey Dahmer ===\n[[Jeffrey Dahmer]] was one of the most notorious American serial killers, sex offenders, and necrophiliacs. His fascination with death was present from childhood, during which he reportedly owned a collection of various bones. In 1978, Dahmer killed the first of several victims, later admitting to having had oral sex with some of them post-mortem. \n\n=== Ted Bundy ===\n[[Ted Bundy]] (born in November 1946) was an American serial killer who raped and murdered many young women during the 1970s. He also confessed to participating in necrophilic acts, claiming to have chosen secluded disposal sites for his victims' bodies specifically for post-mortem sexual intercourse.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Molinari|first=Christina|date=August 2005|title=NECROPHILIC AND NECROPHAGIC SERIAL KILLERS|url=https://fgcu.digital.flvc.org/islandora/object/fgcu%3A27446/datastream/OBJ/view/Necrophilic_and_Necrophagic_Serial_Killers__Understanding_Their_Motivations_through_Case_Study_Analysis.pdf|journal=Florida Gulf Coast University Thesis|pages=59\u201360}}</ref>\n\n=== Karen Greenlee ===\n[[Karen Greenlee]] (born 1956) is a female necrophilic criminal who was convicted of stealing a 1975 Cadillac hearse at a funeral and having sex with the corpse inside of it. She worked as an apprentice embalmer in Sacramento, California. On 17 December 1979, she stole the hearse along with the body of a 33-year-old man that was inside. She was sentenced to pay a $255 fine and 11 days in prison.\n\nIn 1987, Greenlee gave a detailed interview called \u201cThe Unrepentant Necrophile''\u201d for Jim Morton's (edited by [[Adam Parfrey|Adam Parafrey]]) book ''Apocalypse Culture''. In this interview, she stated that she had a preference for younger men and was attracted to the smell of blood and death. She considered necrophilia an addiction. The interview was held in her apartment, which was apparently a small studio filled with books, necrophilic drawings, and satanic adornments. She also had written a confession letter in which she claimed to have abused 20\u201340 male corpses.<ref>{{Citation|last=Crafford|first=J. E.|chapter=The Role of Feral House Mice in Ecosystem Functioning on Marion Island|date=1990|pages=359\u2013364|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|isbn=9783642840760|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-84074-6_40|title=Antarctic Ecosystems}}</ref>\n\n=== Dennis Nilsen ===\n[[Dennis Nilsen]] (born in November 1945) was a Scottish serial killer and necrophiliac who murdered twelve young men between 1978 and 1983.\n\nFollowing the death of his grandfather and his mother's explanation that the dead are in a \"better place,\" Nilsen developed an association between death and intimacy, later finding posing as a corpse a source of sexual arousal. In 1978, Nilsen committed his first murder and enjoyed intercourse with the victim's corpse, keeping the body for months before disposal. Nilsen was reported to have sexually abused the corpses of various victims until his arrest.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Legality==\n===Australia===\n\nNecrophilia is not explicitly mentioned in Australian law, however, under the Crimes Act 1900 \u2013 Sect 81C it states misconduct with regard to corpses is any person who:\n\n(a) indecently interferes with any dead human body, or\n\n(b) improperly interferes with, or offers any indignity to, any dead human body or human remains (whether buried or not),\n\nshall be liable to imprisonment for two years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www6.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/legis/nsw/consol_act/ca190082/s81c.html|title=CRIMES ACT 1900 \u2013 SECT 81C Misconduct with regard to corpses|website=www6.austlii.edu.au|access-date=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Brazil===\n\nArticle 212 of the Brazilian Penal Code (federal Decree-Law No 2.848) states as follows:<ref name=bpc>{{Cite web |url=http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/decreto-lei/Del2848compilado.htm |title=C\u00f3digo Penal (Decreto-Lei n\u00ba 2.848) |publisher=Presidency of the Republic |date=7 December 1940 |accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref><ref>Free translation from Brazilian Portuguese to English.</ref>\n\t\t \n<blockquote>Art. 212 \u2013 To abuse a cadaver or its ashes:<br>Penalty: detention, from 1 to 3 years, plus fine.</blockquote>\n \nAlthough sex with a corpse is not explicitly mentioned, a person who has sex with a corpse may be convicted of a crime under the above Article. The legal asset protected by such Article is not the corpse's objective honour, but the feeling of good memories, respect, and veneration that living people keep about the deceased person: these persons are considered passive subjects of the corpse's violation.\n\n===India===\nSection 297 of the Indian Penal Code entitled \"Trespassing on burial places, etc.\", states as follows:<ref name=\"ipc\">{{cite web|url=http://mynation.net/ipc.htm#_Toc496765169 |title=The Indian Penal Code (IPC): Dowry Law Misuse (IPC 448) By Indian Women |publisher=Mynation.net |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Whoever, with the intention of wounding the feelings of any person, or of insulting the religion of any person, or with the knowledge that the feelings of any person are likely to be wounded, or that the religion of any person is likely to be insulted thereby,\ncommits any trespass in any place of worship or on any place of sculpture, or any place set apart from the performance of funeral rites or as a depository for the remains of the dead, or offers any indignity to any human corpse, or causes disturbance to any persons assembled for the performance of funeral ceremonies, shall be punished with imprisonment of either description for a term which may extend to one year, or with fine, or with both.</blockquote>\n\nAlthough sex with a corpse is not explicitly mentioned, a person who has sex with a corpse may be convicted under the above section. [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] could also be invoked.\n\n===New Zealand===\nUnder Section 150 of the New Zealand [[Crimes Act 1961]], it is an offence for there to be \"misconduct in respect to human remains\". Subsection (b) elaborates that this applies if someone \"improperly or indecently interferes with or offers indignity to any dead human body or human remains, whether buried or not\". This statute is therefore applicable to sex with corpses and carries a potential two-year prison sentence, although there is no relevant case law.<ref>Butterworths Crimes Act 1961: Wellington: Butterworths: 2003</ref>\n\n===South Africa===\nSection 14 of the [[Criminal Law (Sexual Offences and Related Matters) Amendment Act, 2007]] prohibits the commission of a sexual act with a corpse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.za/legislation/acts/2007-032.pdf |title=Criminal Law (Sexual Offences and Related Matters) Amendment Act 32 of 2007 |at=sec. 14 |date=December 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523214416/http://www.justice.gov.za/legislation/acts/2007-032.pdf |archivedate=23 May 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> Until codified by the act it was a [[common law offence]].\n\n===Sweden===\nSection 16, \u00a7 10 of the Swedish Penal Code criminalises necrophilia, but it is not explicitly mentioned. Necrophilia falls under the regulations against abusing a corpse or grave (''brott mot griftefrid''), which carries a maximum sentence of two years in prison. One person has been convicted of necrophilia. He was sentenced to psychiatric care for that and other crimes, including arson.<ref name=\"HD06\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hd.se/2006-10-06/fakta-nekrofili-och-brott-mot-griftefrid |title=Fakta: Nekrofili och brott mot griftefrid |work=HD |access-date=21 September 2017 |language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom ===\nSexual penetration of a corpse was made illegal under the [[Sexual Offences Act 2003]], carrying a maximum sentence of two years' imprisonment. Prior to 2003, necrophilia was not illegal; however, exposing a naked corpse in public was classed as a [[public nuisance]] (''R v. Clark [1883] 15 Cox 171'').{{sfn|Aggrawal|2016|p=200}}\n\n===United States===\nThere is no federal legislation specifically barring sex with a corpse. Multiple states have their own laws:{{sfn|Aggrawal|2010|pp=201\u2013210}}<ref>{{cite book |author1=Posner, Richard A. |author2=Silbaugh, Katharine B. |authorlink2=Katharine Silbaugh | year = 1996 | title = A Guide to America's Sex Laws | publisher = University of Chicago Press | pages = 213\u2013216}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! State\n! Severity\n! Statute\n|-\n| [[Alabama]]\n| [[Felony]] (Class C)\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100316223413/http://www.legislature.state.al.us/CodeofAlabama/1975/13A-11-13.htm \u00a7 13A-11-13]\n|-\n| [[Alaska]]\n| [[Misdemeanor]] (Class A)\n| [http://touchngo.com/lglcntr/akstats/Statutes/Title11/Chapter61/Section130.htm \u00a7 11-61-130]\n|-\n| [[Arizona]]\n| Felony (Class 4)\n| [http://www.azleg.gov/FormatDocument.asp?inDoc=/ars/32/01364.htm&Title=32&DocType=ARS \u00a7 32-1364]\n|-\n| [[Arkansas]]\n| Felony (Class D)\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/arkansas/2010/title-5/subtitle-6/chapter-60/subchapter-1/5-60-101 \u00a7 5-60-101]\n|-\n| [[California]]\n| Felony\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20090505021654/http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/cgi-bin/displaycode?section=hsc&group=07001-08000&file=7050.5-7055 Health and Safety Code \u00a7 7052]\n|-\n| [[Colorado]]\n| Misdemeanor (Class 2)\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20150226130310/http://www.lpdirect.net/casb/crs/18-13-101.html \u00a7 18-13-101]\n|-\n| [[Connecticut]] \n| Misdemeanor (Class A) or Felony (Class D) if victim under 16\n| [https://law.justia.com/codes/connecticut/2005/title53a/sec53a-73a.html \u00a7 53a-73a]\n|-\n| [[Delaware]]\n| Misdemeanor (Class A)\n| [http://delcode.delaware.gov/title11/c005/sc07/index.shtml#1332 \u00a7 11-5-1332]\n|-\n| [[Florida]]\n| Felony (second degree)\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20090301060454/http://www.leg.state.fl.us/STATUTES/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&Search_String=&URL=Ch0872%2FSec06.HTM \u00a7 872.06]\n|-\n| [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| Felony\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/georgia/2010/title-16/chapter-6/16-6-7 \u00a7 16-6-7]\n|-\n| [[Hawaii]]\n| Misdemeanor\n| [http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/hrscurrent/vol14_ch0701-0853/hrs0711/hrs_0711-1108.htm \u00a7 711\u20131108]\n|-\n| [[Idaho]]\n| Misdemeanor\n| [https://legislature.idaho.gov/statutesrules/idstat/Title18/T18CH70/SECT18-7027/ \u00a7 18-7027]\n|-\n| [[Illinois]]\n| Felony (Class 2)\n| [http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/documents/072000050K12-20.6.htm \u00a7 720 ILCS 5/12-20.6]\n|-\n| [[Indiana]]\n| Felony (Level 6)\n| [http://www.in.gov/legislative/ic/2010/title35/ar45/ch11.html \u00a7 35-45-11-2]\n|-\n| [[Iowa]]\n| Felony (Class D)\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100403073337/http://www.legis.state.ia.us/IACODE/1999SUPPLEMENT/709/18.html \u00a7 709.18]\n|-\n|[[Kansas]]\n|Misdemeanor\n|[https://law.justia.com/codes/kansas/2013/chapter-21/article-62/section-21-6205/ \u00a7 21-6205]\n|-\n| [[Kentucky]]\n| Felony (Class D)\n| [http://www.lrc.ky.gov/statutes/statute.aspx?id=19934 \u00a7 525.120]\n|-\n|[[Louisiana]]\n|Misdemeanor\n|[https://law.justia.com/codes/louisiana/2011/rs/title14/rs14-101/ \u00a7 LA Rev Stat 14:101]\n|-\n|[[Maine]]\n|Felony (Class D)\n|[https://legislature.maine.gov/statutes/17-A/title17-A.pdf \u00a7 17.508]\n|-\n|[[Maryland]]\n|Misdemeanor\n|[https://www.dllr.state.md.us/forms/cemdisinterlaw.pdf \u00a7 10-401]\n|-\n|[[Massachusetts]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|[[Michigan]]\n|Misdemeanor\n|[http://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(g2g2r2yddrq1b0hfgvo0avaw))/mileg.aspx?page=GetObject&objectname=mcl-750-160 \u00a7 750.160]\n|-\n| [[Minnesota]]\n| Misdemeanor\n| [https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/?id=609.294 \u00a7 609.294]\n|-\n| [[Mississippi]]\n| Felony\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/mississippi/2013/title-97/chapter-29/in-general/section-97-29-25 \u00a7 97-29-25]\n|-\n|[[Missouri]]\n|Felony (Class D)\n|[https://law.justia.com/codes/missouri/2005/t12/1940000425.html \u00a7 194.425]\n|-\n|[[Montana]]\n|Felony\n|[https://leg.mt.gov/bills/mca/45/5/45-5-627.htm \u00a7 45-5-627]\n|-\n|[[Nebraska]]\n|Felony (Class 4)\n|[https://nebraskalegislature.gov/laws/statutes.php?statute=28-1301 \u00a7 28-1301]\n|-\n| [[Nevada]]\n| Felony (Class A)\n| [http://law.onecle.com/nevada/crimes/201.450.html NRS \u00a7 201.450]\n|-\n|[[New Hampshire]]\n|Misdemeanor\n|[[google:new+hampshire+corpse+abuse&oq=new+hampshire+corpse+abuse+&aqs=chrome..69i57j33l5.10166j1j4&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8|\u00a7 644:7]]\n|-\n|[[New Jersey]]\n|Felony (Class 3)\n|[https://law.justia.com/codes/new-jersey/2013/title-2c/section-2c-22-1/ \u00a7 2C:22-1]\n|-\n|[[New Mexico]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n| [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| Misdemeanor (Class A)\n| [http://public.leginfo.state.ny.us/LAWSSEAF.cgi?QUERYTYPE=LAWS+&QUERYDATA=$$PEN130.20$$@TXPEN0130.20+&LIST=LAW \u00a7 130.20]\n|-\n|[[North Carolina]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n| [[North Dakota]]\n| Misdemeanor (Class A)\n| [http://www.legis.nd.gov/cencode/t12-1c20.pdf?20150226073932 \u00a7 12.1-20-12 and \u00a7 12.1-20-02]\n|-\n| [[Ohio]]\n| Felony (fifth degree)\n| [http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/2927.01 \u00a7 2927.01]\n|-\n|[[Oklahoma]]\n|Felony\n|[https://law.justia.com/codes/oklahoma/2014/title-21/section-21-1161.1 \u00a7 21-1161]\n|-\n| [[Oregon]]\n| Felony\n| [http://www.oregonlaws.org/ors/166.085 ORS \u00a7 166.085]\n|-\n| [[Pennsylvania]]\n| Misdemeanor (second degree)\n| [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.055.010.000..HTM 18 Pa. Cons. Stat. \u00a7 5510]\n|-\n| [[Rhode Island]]\n| Felony\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/rhode-island/2012/title-11/chapter-11-20/chapter-11-20-1.2 \u00a7 11-20-1.2]\n|-\n|[[South Carolina]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|[[South Dakota]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n| [[Tennessee]]\n| Felony (Class E)\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/tennessee/2010/title-39/chapter-17/part-3/39-17-312 \u00a7 39-17-312]\n|-\n| [[Texas]]\n| Misdemeanor (Class A)\n| [http://www.statutes.legis.state.tx.us/Docs/PE/htm/PE.42.htm#42.08 \u00a7 9.42.08]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statutes.legis.state.tx.us/Docs/PE/htm/PE.42.htm#42.08 |title=Texas Penal Code Chapter 42. Disorderly Conduct And Related Offenses |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428190550/http://www.statutes.legis.state.tx.us/Docs/PE/htm/PE.42.htm#42.08|archivedate=28 April 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Utah]]\n| Felony (third degree)\n| [http://law.justia.com/codes/utah/2006/title76/76_0b041.html \u00a7 76-9-704]\n|-\n|[[Vermont]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|[[Virginia]]\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n| [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]]\n| Felony (Class C)\n| [http://apps.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=9A.44.105 RCW \u00a7 9A.44.105]\n|-\n|[[West Virginia]]\n|Misdemeanor\n|[http://www.wvlegislature.gov/wvcode/ChapterEntire.cfm?chap=61&art=8&section=9 \u00a7 61-8-9]\n|-\n| [[Wisconsin]]\n| Felony (Class G)\n| [http://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/statutes/statutes/940/II/225 \u00a7 940.225 (7)]<ref>Although the wording is somewhat ambiguous, the Supreme Court of Wisconsin determined this statute applied to \"sexual contact or sexual intercourse with a victim already dead at the time of the sexual activity when the accused did not cause the death of the victim\" in [http://www.wicourts.gov/sc/opinion/DisplayDocument.html?content=html&seqNo=33332 State v. Grunke].</ref>\n|-\n|[[Wyoming]]\n|Felony\n|[https://law.justia.com/codes/wyoming/2014/title-6/chapter-4/article-5/section-6-4-502/ \u00a7 6-4-502]\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [[Incidents of necrophilia]]\n* [[Necrophilia in popular culture]]\n* [[Vulnerability and care theory of love]]\n* [[Death during consensual sex]]\n* [[Karen Greenlee]]\n* [[Sir Jimmy Savile]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book | first=Anil |last= Aggrawal| date = 2010 | title = Necrophilia: Forensic and Medico-legal Aspects | publisher = CRC Press |location=Boca Raton, Florida| isbn= 978-1420089127|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Aggrawal|first=Anil|title=Necrophilia: Forensic and Medico-legal Aspects|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b0k2qpfyU8IC|date=19 April 2016|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4200-8913-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Finbow|first=Steve|title=Grave Desire: A Cultural History of Necrophilia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rGIpBQAAQBAJ|date=2014|publisher=Winchester, UK: Zero Books|isbn=978-1-7827-9342-7|ref=harv}}\n*Lee Mellor (2016) Homicide: A Forensic Psychology Casebook. CRC Press. {{ISBN|9781498731522}}.\n*{{cite book|last1=Purcell|first1=Catherine|last2=Arrigo|first2=Bruce A.|title=The Psychology of Lust Murder: Paraphilia, Sexual Killing, and Serial Homicide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=agmkfIgbQxUC|date=7 June 2006|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-08-046257-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=West|first1=Sarah G.|last2=Resnick|first2=Phillip J.|chapter=Necrophilia|title=Unusual and Rare Psychological Disorders: A Handbook for Clinical Practice and Research|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dgc1DQAAQBAJ|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-024586-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Lisa Downing]], ''Desiring the Dead: Necrophilia and Nineteenth-Century French Literature''. Oxford: Legenda, 2003\n*[[Richard von Krafft-Ebing]], ''Psychopathia Sexualis''. New York: Stein & Day, 1965. Originally published in 1886.\n\n=== In literature ===\n\n*[[Gabrielle Wittkop]], ''The Necrophiliac'', 1972\n*[[Barbara Gowdy]], ''We So Seldom Look on Love'', 1992\n*[[Frank O'Hara]], ''Ode on Necrophilia'', 1960\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB     =\n|  ICD10          = {{ICD10|F|65.8}} \n}}\n{{Paraphilia}}\n{{Death}}\n{{Human sexuality}}\n{{Sexual ethics}}\n{{Sex fetish}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Necrophilia| ]]\n[[Category:Paraphilias]]\n[[Category:Sex crimes]]\n", "name_user": "Clarkejryan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copy edited in the top section and 'Origins of term'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Necrophilia"}
{"title_page": "Jaguarundi", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jaguarundi\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |author=Caso, A. |author2=de Oliveira, T. |author3=Carvajal, S.V. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T9948A50653167 |year=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Herpailurus yagouaroundi Jaguarundi ZOO D\u011b\u010d\u00edn.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[Nikolai Severtzov|Severtzov]], 1858\n| taxon = Herpailurus yagouaroundi\n| authority = ([[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire|Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]], 1803)\n| synonyms = \n{{collapsible list |bullets=true\n |''Felis yagouaroundi'' <small>Geoffroy, 1803</small>\n |''Puma yaguaroundi''  <small>Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1809</small>\n |''F. eyra'' <small>Fischer, 1814</small>\n |''F. unicolor'' <small>Thraill, 1819</small>\n |''F. cacomitli'' <small>Berlandier, 1859</small>\n |''F. apache'' <small>[[Edgar Alexander Mearns|Mearns]], 1901</small>\n |''F. fossata'' <small>Mearns, 1901</small>\n |''F. panamensis'' <small>[[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1904</small>\n}}\n| range_map =Jaguarundi distribution.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of the jaguarundi (2015)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''jaguarundi''' (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'') ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) is a wild [[felidae|cat]] native to the Americas. Its range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the [[Andes]]. The jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats (such as the small, spotted cats in the [[genus]] ''[[Leopardus]]'') in its external appearance. In fact, the jaguarundi shows several features seen in [[mustelid]]s (such as [[otter]]s and [[weasel]]s)\u2014it has an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. There are two color [[Morph (zoology)|morph]]s\u2014gray and red.\n\nSecretive and alert, the jaguarundi is typically solitary or forms pairs in the wild, though captive individuals are gregarious. Unlike other [[Sympatry|sympatric]] cats such as [[ocelot]]s, the jaguarundi is more active during the day and hunts mainly during daytime and evening hours. Individuals live in large [[home range]]s, and are sparsely distributed within a region. Though an efficient climber and swimmer, the jaguarundi typically prefers hunting on ground. It feeds on various kinds of prey, especially ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Mating occurs throughout the year, with peaks at different times of the year across the range. After a [[gestation period]] of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens. Lifespan of up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.\n\nJaguarundis occur in a broad array of closed as well as open habitats ranging from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. While they are fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela, jaguarundis may have gone [[extinct]] in the US. The [[IUCN]] lists the jaguarundi as [[Least Concern]], but populations are in decline in many parts of its range due to loss and [[Habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] of their habitat and persecution for killing poultry.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe common name \"jaguarundi\" ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) comes from the [[Guarani language|Old Guarani]] word ''yaguarundi'', similar to the [[Old Tupi]] word ''yawaum'di''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferreira |first=A.B.H. |year=1986 |title=Novo Dicion\u00e1rio da L\u00edngua Portuguesa|language=Portuguese |trans-title=New Dictionary of the Portuguese Language |edition=2nd|place=Rio de Janeiro |publisher=Nova Fronteira |page=980}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|jaguarundi|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> In some [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the jaguarundi is also called ''gato colorado'', ''gato moro'', ''le\u00f3n brenero'', ''leoncillo'' and ''tigrillo''.<ref name=iucn/> It is also called ''eyra'', ''gato-mourisco'', ''gato-preto'', ''gato-vermelho'' and ''maracaj\u00e1-preto'' in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=de Miranda |first1=E.E. |last2=Gambarini |first2=A. |title=Natureza, Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o e Cultura: Ensaio sobre a Rela\u00e7\u00e3o do Homem com a Natureza no Brasil |trans-title=Nature, Conservation and Culture: Essay on the Relationship between Man and Nature in Brazil |date=2003 |publisher=Metalivros |location=S\u00e3o Paulo |isbn=9788585371470 |page=113 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Nowell |editor1-first=K. |editor2-last=Jackson |editor2-first=P. |editor3-last=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |date=1996 |publisher=IUCN |location=Gland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |page=146}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis yagouarundi'' was the [[scientific name]] used by [[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]] in 1803 who described two [[zoological specimen|specimen]]s from Central America, including one from [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, \u00c9. |authorlink=\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire |year=1803 |title=Catalogue des Mammif\u00e8res du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |trans-title=Catalogue of Mammals of the National Museum of Natural History| language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |page=124 |chapter=Le chat yagouarundi. ''Felis yagouarundi'' (The cat jaguarundi: ''Felis yagouarundi'')|chapter-url={{Google Books|id=951AAAAAcAAJ|page=124|plainurl=yes}} }}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several more specimens, presumably jaguarundis, were described:\n*''Felis eyra'' proposed by [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim]] in 1814 was a [[rust (color)|ferruginous]] skin from [[Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Fischer von Waldheim, G. |authorlink=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim |year=1814 |title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata : in usum praelectionum Academiae imperialis medico-chirugicae mosquensis edita |language=Latin |location=Moscow |publisher=Nicolai S. Vsevolozsky |page=228 |chapter=''Felis eyra'' |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc/page/228}}</ref>\n*[[Gulf Coast Jaguarundi|''F. cacomitli'']] proposed by [[Jean-Louis Berlandier]] in 1859 was a skull and a grayish skin of a female from the [[Rio Grande]] area in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Berlandier, J.-L. |authorlink=Jean-Louis Berlandier |year=1859 |title=Report on the United States and Mexican boundary survey made under the direction of the Secretary of the Interior |volume=II. Mammals of the boundary |editor1=Baird, S. F. |location=Washington |publisher=A.O.P. Nicholson |pages=12\u201313 |chapter=''Felis yagouarundi'' (Desm.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKogAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA12#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi tolteca'' proposed by [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1898 was a skull and a reddish skin from [[Sinaloa]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas |year=1898 |title=On new mammals from Western Mexico and Lower California |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=7 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201346 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof711898lond/page/40}}</ref>\n*''F. ameghinoi'' proposed by [[Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg]] in 1898 for bones, presumably of a jaguarundi, found near [[San Luis, Argentina]], which are embalmed in the [[Turin Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Holmberg, E. L. |authorlink=Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg |year=1898 |chapter=La fauna de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina (The fauna of the Argentine Republic) |pages=477\u2013602 |title=Segundo Censo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina Mayo 10 de 1895 |trans-title=Second Census of the Argentine Republic May 10, 1895 |volume=1 |editor=Carrasco, G. |publisher=Taller Tipogr\u00e1fico de la Penitenciar\u00eda Nacional |location=Buenos Aires }}</ref>\n*''F. fossata'' by [[Edgar Alexander Mearns]] in 1901 was a large skull from [[Yucat\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mearns, E.A. |authorlink=Edgar Alexander Mearns |year=1901 |title=Two new cats of the eyra group from North America |volume=14 |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |pages=149\u2013151 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio14biol/page/148}}</ref>\n*''F. panamensis'' by [[Joel Asaph Allen]] in 1904 was a dusky gray skin of a young adult female collected in Panama's [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J.A. |authorlink=Joel Asaph Allen |year=1904 |title=Mammals from southern Mexico and Central and South America |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=29\u201380 |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/662//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/bul/B020a04.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi melantho'' by Oldfield Thomas in 1914 were skulls and blackish brown skins of a male and a female from [[Pozuzo District|Pozuzu]] in Peru.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1914 |title=On various South-American mammals |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=13 |issue=75 |pages=345\u2013363 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof1319unse/page/350}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Genus (biology)|generic]] name ''Herpailurus'' was proposed by [[Nikolai Severtzov]] in 1858 for the jaguarundi.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Severtzov |first1=N.A. |authorlink=Nikolai Severtzov |year=1858 |title=Notice sur la classification multis\u00e9riale des carnivores, sp\u00e9cialement des F\u00e9lid\u00e9s, et les \u00e9tudes de zoologie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale qui s'y rattachent |trans-title=Notes on the classification of the carnivores, especially the Felidae, and the respective zoological studies |journal=Revue et Magasin de Zoologie Pure et Appliqu\u00e9e |volume=X |language=French| pages=385\u2013396 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revueetmagasinde10soci#page/390/mode/2up}}</ref> Later authors classified the jaguarundi in the genus ''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]'' along with the [[cougar]] (''P. concolor'').<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000211 |heading=Species ''Puma yagouaroundi'' |page=545}}</ref> In 2017, the [[IUCN]] Cat Specialist Group listed the jaguarundi as a [[monotypic taxon]] of the genus ''Herpailurus''.<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |display-authors=23 |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref> [[Phylogeography|Phylogeographical]] analysis of jaguarundi samples from across its range found no genetic evidence for [[subspecies]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |author2=Pinedo-Castro, M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |pages=245\u2013288 |chapter=Population genetics and phylogeographic analyses of the jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') by means of three mitochondrial markers: The first molecular study of this species |title=Molecular Population Genetics, Evolutionary Biology and Biological Conservation on Neotropical Carnivores |editor1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |editor2=Shostell, J. M. |publisher=Nova Publishers |location=New York |isbn=978-1-62417-079-9 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/230597248_Population_genetics_and_phylogeographic_of_the_jaguarundi_Puma_yaguaroundi_by_means_of_three_mitochondrial_markers_the_first_molecular_population_study_of_this_species_Chapter_8_Molecular_Population_G}}</ref>\n\n==Phylogeny and evolution==\n{{cladogram|title=\n|align=left\n|caption=The ''Puma'' lineage of the family [[Felidae]], depicted along with closely related genera.<ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W.E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae) |year=2010 |pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142 |editor1-last=Macdonald |editor1-first=D.W. |editor2-last=Loveridge |editor2-first=A.J. |title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-19-923445-5 |edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n|1={{clade | style=font-size:90%;line-height:100%;width:450px;\n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |label1=''Lynx'' lineage\n         |1=''[[Lynx (genus)|Lynx]]''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{clade\n            |label1=''Puma'' lineage\n            |1={{clade\n               |label1=''[[Acinonyx]]''\n               |1= ''Acinonyx jubatus'' <br/>([[Cheetah]]) |image1=[[File:Cynailurus guttata - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam - (white background).jpg|80px|left]]\n               |2={{clade\n                  |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n                  |1=''Puma concolor'' <br/>([[Cougar]]) |image1=[[File:Felis concolor - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam -(white background).jpg|70px|left]]\n                  |label2='''''Herpailurus'''''&nbsp;\n                  |2=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' <br/>('''Jaguarundi''')\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=Domestic cat lineage\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''\n            |label2=Leopard cat lineage\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Otocolobus]]''\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n}}\n\nThe jaguarundi is most closely related to the cougar and [[cheetah]].<ref name=\"Culver\">{{cite journal |author1=Culver, M. |author2=Johnson, W. E. |author3=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author4=O'Brien, S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2000 |title=Genomic Ancestry of the American Puma |journal=[[Journal of Heredity]] |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186 |pmid=10833043 |url-status=dead |url=http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616200443/http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> These three species together form the ''Puma'' lineage, one of the eight lineages of Felidae; the ''Puma'' lineage [[Genetic divergence|diverged]] from the rest 6.7 [[Mya (unit)|mya]]. The [[sister group]] of the ''Puma'' lineage is a [[clade]] of smaller [[Old World]] cats that includes the genera ''[[Felis]]'', ''[[Otocolobus]]'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]''.<ref name=\"werdelin\"/> \n\nThe three species of the ''Puma'' lineage may have had a [[common ancestor]] during the [[Miocene]], about {{mya|8.25}}.<ref name=\"adams\">{{cite journal |last1=Adams |first1=D. B. |title=The cheetah: native American |journal=Science |year=1979 |volume=205 |issue=4411 |pages=1155\u20131158 |doi=10.1126/science.205.4411.1155 |pmid=17735054 |bibcode=1979Sci...205.1155A |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6901/86b75e66b681ff0d83772f74068cd1b908b5.pdf}}</ref><ref name=johnson>{{cite journal |pmid=9071018 |year=1997 |last1=Johnson |first1=W. E. |last2=O'Brien |first2=S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Phylogenetic reconstruction of the Felidae using 16S rRNA and NADH-5 mitochondrial genes |volume=44 |issue=S1 |pages=S98\u2013S116 |journal=Journal of Molecular Evolution |doi=10.1007/PL00000060|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232587 |bibcode=1997JMolE..44S..98J}}</ref> ''Acinonyx'' possibly diverged from the lineage in the Americas;<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal |last1=Johnson |first1=W.E. |last2=Eizirik |first2=E. |last3=Pecon-Slattery |first3=J. |last4=Murphy |first4=W.J. |last5=Antunes |first5=A. |last6=Teeling |first6=E. |last7=O'Brien |first7=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |doi=10.1126/science.1122277 |title=The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=311 |pages=73\u201377 |pmid=16400146 |issue=5757 |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1230866}}</ref><ref name=dobrynin>{{cite journal |last1=Dobrynin |first1=P. |last2=Liu |first2=S. |last3=Tamazian |first3 = G. |last4=Xiong |first4=Z. |last5=Yurchenko |first5=A. A. |last6=Krasheninnikova |first6=K. |last7=Kliver |first7=S. |last8=Schmidt-K\u00fcntzel |first8=A. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genomic legacy of the African cheetah, ''Acinonyx jubatus'' |journal=Genome Biology |year=2015 |volume=16 |pages=277 |doi=10.1186/s13059-015-0837-4 |pmid=26653294 |pmc=4676127}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Brien |first1=S. J. |last2=Johnson |first2=W. E. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The evolution of cats |journal=Scientific American |date=2007 |volume=297 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201375 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0707-68 |url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/O%27brien2007EvolutionCats.pdf}}</ref> some authors alternatively suggest that the cheetah diverged in the Old World.<ref>{{cite journal |first=R. |last=Barnett |author2=I. B. |author3=Phillips, M. J. |author4=Martin, L. D. |author5=Harington, C. R. |author6=Leonard, J. A. |author7=Cooper, A. |year=2005 |title=Evolution of the extinct Sabretooths and the American cheetah-like cat |journal=[[Current Biology]] |volume=15 |issue=15 |pages=R589\u2013R590 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2005.07.052 |pmid=16085477}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faurby |first1=S. |last2=Werdelin |first2=L. |last3=Svenning |first3=J. C. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The difference between trivial and scientific names: there were never any true cheetahs in North America |journal=Genome Biology |year=2016 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=89 |doi=10.1186/s13059-016-0943-y|pmid=27150269 |pmc=4858926}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Puma'' lineage appears to have migrated from Asia to North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]], arriving in South America via the [[Isthmus of Panama]] by [[Late Pliocene]] or [[Early Pleistocene]]. This was possibly followed by the bifurcation of the lineage into the cougar and ''Herpailurus'' (represented by ''H. pumoides'') in South America around {{mya|4|3}} between the Late Pliocene and Early Pleistocene. ''H. pumoides'' went extinct around [[Middle Pleistocene]], around the time the modern jaguarundi came into existence; the oldest fossils of the modern jaguarundi date back to the [[Late Pleistocene]] in Brazil around {{mya|0.5}}. The original North American cougars were extripated during the [[Pleistocene extinctions]] around 10,000 years ago; then North America was recolonized by South American cougars and jaguarundis 10,000\u20138,000 years ago.<ref name=bellani/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Culver |first1=M. |title=Genomic ancestry of the American puma (''Puma concolor'') |journal=Journal of Heredity |date=2000 |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chimento |first1=N.R. |last2=Dondas |first2=A. |title=First record of ''Puma concolor'' (Mammalia, Felidae) in the Early-Middle Pleistocene of South America |journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution |date=2017 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=381\u2013389 |doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9385-x}}</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header    = \n| header_align = center\n\n| image1    = Jaguarondi 2.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = <center>Red morph</center>\n\n| image2    = Jaguarundi seitlich.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  = <center>Gray morph</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}} \nThe jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats in its external appearance. This has been attributed to variations in its [[karyotype]]\u2014the jaguarundi has 38 [[chromosome]]s, unlike the 36 in other small South American cats, and the chromosomal features resemble those of Old World cats such as the [[leopard cat]] (''Prionailurus bengalensis'').<ref name=WCoW/> Interestingly, the jaguarundi is characterized by several [[mustelid]] features\u2014an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. As such, the jaguarundi is sometimes considered similar to [[marten]]s, [[otter]]s or [[weasel]]s.<ref name=\"bellani\">{{cite book |last1=Bellani |first1=G.G. |title=Felines of the World: Discoveries in Taxonomic Classification and History |date=2020 |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-12-816503-4 |pages=223-231 |url={{Google Books|id=xK2wDwAAQBAJ|page=223|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|page=818|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=818|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The head-and-body length is between {{convert|53|and|77|cm|in|abbr=on}}; the strong, muscular tail is {{convert|31|\u2013|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though larger individuals weighing around {{convert|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}} have been reported.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |author1=Sunquist, M. |author2=Sunquist, F. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild Cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |pages=113\u2013119 |isbn= 978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/113}}</ref><ref name=\"fws.gov\">{{Cite journal |author1=Brown, D.E. |author2=Gonzalez, C.A. |year=1999 |title=Jaguarundi (''Felis yagouaroundi tolteca'') |url=http://www.fws.gov/southwest/es/Arizona/Documents/Redbook/Jaguarundi%20RB.pdf |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |issue=32 |pages=155\u2013157}}</ref> Males are slightly larger than females.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nThe coat is uniformly colored with at most a few faint markings on the face and the belly, though kittens may be spotted for a short duration. Black and white marks on the lips and the snout, similar to those of the cougar, can be clearly seen in juveniles and some adults. The fur color varies from blackish to brownish-grey with a grizzled look due to alternating bright and dark rings on individual hairs (called gray [[Morph (biology)|morph]]), to foxy red to chestnut (called red morph); earlier these morphs were considered two different species. Individuals of both colors can be born in the same litter.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=\"hildyard\">{{cite book |last1=Sirimarco |first1=E. |editor1-last=Hildyard |editor1-first=A. |title=Endangered Wildlife and Plants of the World (Volume 6) |date=2001 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Co |location=New York |isbn=0-7614-7200-2 |pages=736-738 |chapterurl={{Google Books|plainurl=yes|id=5YYqd4ROFfkC|page=736}} |chapter=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yaguarondi cacomitli'')}}</ref> Blackish brown individuals superficially resemble the [[tayra]] (''Eira barbara''), but the latter can be told apart by the clear, yellowish patch on the throat.<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite journal |last1=de Oliveira |first1=T.G. |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |journal=Mammalian Species |date=1998 |issue=578 |pages=1-6 |doi=10.2307/3504500 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275737351_Herpailurus_yagouaroundi}}</ref> The red morph is seen more often in dry, open areas. [[Melanism|melanistic]] individuals have been reported, but they are not completely black; the head and the throat are clearly paler than the rest of the body.<ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=152\u2013156|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=152|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref>  The ears, {{convert|2.5|\u2013|4|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, are widely spaced and, unlike many other felids, lack white spots on the back.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos>{{cite book |author1-last=Aranda |author1-first=M. |author2-last=Caso |author2-first=A. |editor1-last=Ceballos |editor1-first=G. |title=Mammals of Mexico |publisher=John Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-1-4214-0879-8 |pages=498-499 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl={{Google Books|page=498|plainurl=yes|id=UrvxBQAAQBAJ}}}}</ref> The jaguarundi has a total of 30 teeth; the [[dental formula]] is {{DentalFormula|upper=3.1.3.1|lower=3.1.2.1}}.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nAmong felids, the jaguarundi is closely similar to the [[flat-headed cat]] (''Prionailurus planiceps''), but has a longer body and proportionately longer legs, is heavier and lacks the dark markings on the cheeks of the flat-headed cat.<ref name=ms/> Tawny jaguarundis bear a similar coloration as the signficantly larger cougar.<ref name=Hunter/>\n\n==Behavior and ecology==\n[[File:Jaguarondi 1.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are good climbers and can easily walk on branches.]]\nThe jaguarundi is shy and reclusive, and apparently very cautious of [[Animal trapping|traps]].<ref name=Simberloff/> There have been only a few [[radio telemetry]] studies of jaguarundis in Belize, Brazil and Mexico.<ref name=Hunter/> Though activity has been observed throughout the day and at night, jaguarundis seem to prefer hunting during daytime and evening hours; a study in Belize reported that jaguarundis started moving before dawn and remained active through most of the day till sunset with a peak in hunting from late morning to noon.<ref name=ms/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Konecny |first1=M.J. |title=Movement patterns and food habits of four sympatric carnivore species in Belize, South America |journal=Advances in Neotropical Mammalogy |date=1989 |pages=243-264 |url=http://library.bfreebz.org/Mammals/Michael%20Konecny,%20Movement%20Patterns%20and%20Food%20Habits%20of%20Four%20Sympatric%20Carnivore%20Species%20in%20Belize,%20Central%20America,%201989.pdf}}</ref> The cat appears to be more [[Diurnality|diurnal]] than most other cats, especially spotted cats that tend to be more active at night.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=WCoW/> The jaguarundi can swim across medium-sized rivers; an individual was recorded swimming across the [[Tuichi River]] (Bolivia).<ref name=Hunter/> Jaguarundis are efficient climbers as well, but hunt mainly on ground; its coat color works as a good camouflage for terrestrial activity.<ref name=Nowak/> They can leap up to {{convert|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} into the air to catch birds.<ref name=WCoW/> Predators recorded for jaguarundis include [[boa constrictor]]s, cougars and [[domestic dog]]s.<ref name=Hunter/> Parasites such as [[hookworm]]s (''[[Ancylostoma]]'' species), [[tapeworm]]s (such as  ''[[Spirometra]]'' and ''[[Toxocara]]'' species) and the [[lung fluke]] have been found in jaguarundis.<ref name=ms/>\n\nStudies have mostly observed jaguarundis alone or in pairs; pairs could probably be formed between mothers and older kittens or between individuals of opposite sexes during the mating season. Individuals in captivity have been found to be more gregarious.<ref name=WCoW/> [[Home range]]s tend to be large; a study in Brazil recorded home ranges {{convert|1.4|\u2013|18|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size for females, while those of males measured {{convert|8.5|\u2013|25.3|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in area.<ref name=Hunter/> Two males in Belize were recorded to have exceptionally large home ranges spanning an area of {{convert|88|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} and {{convert|100|sqkm|sqmi}}, while the home range of a female in the same region measured {{convert|13|\u2013|20|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size.<ref name=Nowak/> Population densities are typically low, around {{convert|0.01|to|0.05|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}, though the Llanos in Costa Rica and Venezuela have recorded figures as high as {{convert|0.2|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=bellani/>\n\nMarking behavior could serve as a means of olfactory or visual communication; individuals in captivity have been observed scraping areas with their hind feet (sometimes with urination), clawing on logs, rubbing objects with their heads and leaving feces uncovered. Social behavior such as grooming, growling and sniffing has been recorded. The jaguarundi has a broad vocal repertoire; 13 different calls have been recorded including chattering, purring, screaming, a 'wah-wah' call, whistling, yapping and a peculiar bird-like chirp. In captivity, females in [[estrus]] have been observed making faint sounds as they [[scent mark]] the area around their enclosures.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/> \n\n===Diet===\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi, ZOO Praha 254.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are [[Generalist and specialist species|generalist]] carnivores.]]\nThe jaguarundi typically feed on small-sized prey weighing less than {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, including ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Jaguarundis will also take larger prey such as domestic poultry, fish, [[marmoset]]s, rabbits and [[opossum]]s; a study recorded small deer (possibly [[carrion]]) in the diet. Vegetation such as grasses have also been recorded in their diet.<ref name=Hunter/><ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/><ref name=ms/> A study showed jaguarundis take {{convert|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} vertebrate prey on an average everyday.<ref name=ms/> The broad array of prey recorded for the jaguarundi across its range and varying proportions of different prey in its diet could indicate that the cat tends to feed on the most abundant and easily catchable prey in the area.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nJaguarundis have been observed mating all year round, with peaks at different times of the year across the range; for instance, in Mexico breeding peaks in January and March. Estrus lasts three to five days, marked by the female regularly rolling onto her back and [[spraying urine]]. [[Sexually mature]] males will pursue the female, not reacting to any aggressive behavior from her side. As in many other felids, the male bites the fur on the female's neck on mounting; the female lets out a loud scream on penetration.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/>\n\nAfter a [[gestation]] period of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens in a den constructed in a dense thicket, hollow tree, or similar cover. The kittens are covered well with fur and the underside is marked with spots, which disappear as they age; the coat color gradually changes as the kittens grow older.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/> The mother starts bringing solid food for the kittens when they are around three weeks old, who simply play with it till the mother ingests it; kittens are capable of taking solid food like birds and guinea pigs at around six weeks. Jaguarundis become sexually mature at one to three years of age. Lifespan up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=Nowak/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe jaguarundi inhabits a wide variety of habitats\u2014from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. It can also occur in [[cloud forest]]s, [[mangrove]]s and [[savanna]]s.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=ceballos/> Unlike the [[Sympatry|sympatric]] [[margay]], [[ocelot]] and [[oncilla]], the jaguarundi can occur in open areas as well. In open habitats the jaguarundi prefers areas with vegetative cover such as cacti, which would generally be difficult for possible predators to penetrate; there may be a few clearings at the periphery of such areas. Jaguarundis tend to stay close to a source of running water.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=fws.gov/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Coronado-Quibrera |first1=W.P. |last2=Olmos-Oropeza |first2=G. |last3=Bender |first3=L.C. |last4=Rosas-Rosas |first4=O.C. |last5=Palacio-N\u00fa\u00f1ez |first5=J. |last6=Tarango-Ar\u00e1mbula |first6=L.A. |last7=Herrera-Haro |first7=J.G. |title=Adaptability of the threatened jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Schereber, 1777) to human-altered environments in San Luis Potos\u00ed, Mexico |journal=Acta Zool\u00f3gica Mexicana |date=2019 |volume=35 |pages=1\u201315 |doi=10.21829/azm.2019.3502210 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/310f/6597fd914eb664e160637b4b1b1d57d87fe7.pdf}}</ref> The jaguarundi is noted for its resistance to environmental disturbances in its habitat; it can successfully thrive in reforested areas.<ref name=ceballos/> While commonly inhabiting lowlands up to {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the sea level, this cat has been reported at elevations as high as {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Colombia.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThe range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the Andes\u2014second only to the cougar in the [[Latitude|latitudinal]] extent of its distribution. However, not all parts of its range have been studied well. The jaguarundi is fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela.<ref name=\"rev\">{{cite journal |last1=Giordano |first1=A.J. |title=Ecology and status of the jaguarundi ''Puma yagouaroundi'': a synthesis of existing knowledge |journal=Mammal Review |date=2016 |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201343 |doi=10.1111/mam.12051 |url=https://carnivores.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Giordano_2015_mam12051_Jaguarundi.pdf}}</ref> It is possibly [[extinct]] in the US;<ref name=iucn/> a study in 1999 refuted claims of sightings in Arizona.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=D.E. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez |first2=C.A.L. |title=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Geoffroy 1803) not in Arizona or Sonora |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |date=1999 |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=155-157 |jstor=40021308}}</ref> The last confirmed sighting in the US was probably of a roadkilled individual near [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] (Texas) in 1986.<ref name=rev/>\n\nJaguarundis have been sighted in [[Florida]] since the early 20th century; their presence there is attributed to a writer from [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]] who at some point imported the animals from their native habitat and released them near his hometown and in other locations across the state. Several sightings have been reported since 1907; in 1977 [[W. T. Neill]] noted that the population was declining. Jaguarundis have also been reported in the coastal area of [[Alabama]] since the 1980s, which may be evidence of the Florida population migrating northward.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title=Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida |last1=Simberloff |first1=D. |authorlink=Daniel Simberloff |author2=Schmitz, D.C. |author3=Brown, T.C. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1997 |publisher=Island Press |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-55963-430-4 |url={{Google Books |plainurl=yes|page=172|id=rtrpSllq4SQC}} |pages=172\u2013173}}</ref> The jaguarundi has also been recorded from [[Cerro Largo Department|Cerro Largo]] in [[Uruguay]], where its presence was doubted.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Grattarola, F. |author2=Hernandez, D. |author3=Duarte, A. |author4=Gaucher, L. |author5=Perazza, G. |display-authors=3 |year=2016 |title=Primer registro de yaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) en Uruguay, con comentarios sobre monitereo participativo |journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Zool\u00f3gica del Uruguay |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=85\u221291 |language=Spanish |trans-title=First record of jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) in Uruguay, with comments on participatory monitoring}}</ref>\n\n==Threats and conservation==\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi.jpg|thumb|left|Captive jaguarundi in the Zoo de Pont-Scorff (France)]]\nThe jaguarundi has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2002. Mexican populations, except those in the northeast, appear to be stable. The huge reserves of the [[Amazon Basin]] are probably the only conservation units that can sustain long-term viable populations. In its 2015 revision, the IUCN noted that the species should be listed as [[Near Threatened]], but there was not enough data to go upon to extend this classification throughout the range.<ref name=iucn/> The jaguarundi is not particularly sought after for its fur due to its poor quality and low value, but is suffering decline due to habitat loss.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=fws.gov/> Other threats include risks of [[habitat fragmentation]] and persecution for killing poultry.<ref name=iucn/> The North and Central American populations of the jaguarundi are listed in [[CITES Appendix I]] and all the other populations are listed in [[CITES Appendix II]].<ref name=ceballos/> Populations in the US are protected under the [[Endangered Species Act]];<ref name=MSW3/> the [[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]] has expressed concern that its presence in South Texas may be imperiled due to loss of the cat's native habitat.<ref name=Texas2003>{{cite web |url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/landwater/land/habitats/southtx_plain/endangered_species/ |title=Endangered Species |website=Tpwd.state.tx.us |date=2003-04-15 |access-date=2011-09-15 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Populations in Mexico are listed under the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lorenzo |first1=C. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez-Ruiz |first2=N. |title=Mammals in the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010 |journal=Therya |date=2018 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=69\u201372 |doi=10.12933/therya-18-565 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323250093_Mammals_in_the_Mexican_Official_Norm_NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010}}</ref> Hunting jaguarundi is restricted in Peru and banned in Argentina, Belize, Brazil, Bolivia, Colombia, Costa Rica, French Guiana, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Panama, Paraguay, Suriname, Uruguay, the US and Venezuela.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Acinonychini]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons and category|Puma yagouaroundi|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=93 |title=Jaguarundi ''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |website=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group}}\n* {{cite web |website=Big Cats Online |url=http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031107150747/http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-date=2003-11-07 |df=dmy-all |title=Jaguarundi |series=Wild Cat Species and Distribution \u2013 South America}}\n* {{cite Americana |wstitle=Jaguarondi |short=x}}\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q182304}}\n\n[[Category:Puma (genus)]]\n[[Category:Felids of Central America]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Felids of South America]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Belize]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of French Guiana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Honduras]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Suriname]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Panama]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Peru]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Fauna of northern South America]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1803]]\n[[Category:Guaran\u00ed words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jaguarundi\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |author=Caso, A. |author2=de Oliveira, T. |author3=Carvajal, S.V. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T9948A50653167 |year=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Herpailurus yagouaroundi Jaguarundi ZOO D\u011b\u010d\u00edn.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[Nikolai Severtzov|Severtzov]], 1858\n| taxon = Herpailurus yagouaroundi\n| authority = ([[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire|Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]], 1803)\n| synonyms = \n{{collapsible list |bullets=true\n |''Felis yagouaroundi'' <small>Geoffroy, 1803</small>\n |''Puma yaguaroundi''  <small>Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1809</small>\n |''F. eyra'' <small>Fischer, 1814</small>\n |''F. unicolor'' <small>Thraill, 1819</small>\n |''F. cacomitli'' <small>Berlandier, 1859</small>\n |''F. apache'' <small>[[Edgar Alexander Mearns|Mearns]], 1901</small>\n |''F. fossata'' <small>Mearns, 1901</small>\n |''F. panamensis'' <small>[[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1904</small>\n}}\n| range_map =Jaguarundi distribution.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of the jaguarundi (2015)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''jaguarundi''' (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'') ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) is a wild [[felidae|cat]] native to the Americas. Its range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the [[Andes]]. The jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats (such as the small, spotted cats in the [[genus]] ''[[Leopardus]]'') in its external appearance. In fact, the jaguarundi shows several features seen in [[mustelid]]s (such as [[otter]]s and [[weasel]]s)\u2014it has an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. There are two color [[Morph (zoology)|morph]]s\u2014gray and red.\n\nSecretive and alert, the jaguarundi is typically solitary or forms pairs in the wild, though captive individuals are gregarious. Unlike other [[Sympatry|sympatric]] cats such as [[ocelot]]s, the jaguarundi is more active during the day and hunts mainly during daytime and evening hours. Individuals live in large [[home range]]s, and are sparsely distributed within a region. Though an efficient climber and swimmer, the jaguarundi typically prefers hunting on ground. It feeds on various kinds of prey, especially ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Mating occurs throughout the year, with peaks at different times of the year across the range. After a [[gestation period]] of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens. Lifespan of up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.\n\nJaguarundis occur in a broad array of closed as well as open habitats ranging from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. While they are fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela, jaguarundis may have gone [[extinct]] in the US. The [[IUCN]] lists the jaguarundi as [[Least Concern]], but populations are in decline in many parts of its range due to loss and [[Habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] of their habitat and persecution for killing poultry.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe common name \"jaguarundi\" ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}}) comes from the [[Guarani language|Old Guarani]] word ''yaguarundi'', similar to the [[Old Tupi]] word ''yawaum'di''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferreira |first=A.B.H. |year=1986 |title=Novo Dicion\u00e1rio da L\u00edngua Portuguesa|language=Portuguese |trans-title=New Dictionary of the Portuguese Language |edition=2nd|place=Rio de Janeiro |publisher=Nova Fronteira |page=980}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|jaguarundi|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> In some [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the jaguarundi is also called ''gato colorado'', ''gato moro'', ''le\u00f3n brenero'', ''leoncillo'' and ''tigrillo''.<ref name=iucn/> It is also called ''eyra'', ''gato-mourisco'', ''gato-preto'', ''gato-vermelho'' and ''maracaj\u00e1-preto'' in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=de Miranda |first1=E.E. |last2=Gambarini |first2=A. |title=Natureza, Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o e Cultura: Ensaio sobre a Rela\u00e7\u00e3o do Homem com a Natureza no Brasil |trans-title=Nature, Conservation and Culture: Essay on the Relationship between Man and Nature in Brazil |date=2003 |publisher=Metalivros |location=S\u00e3o Paulo |isbn=9788585371470 |page=113 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Nowell |editor1-first=K. |editor2-last=Jackson |editor2-first=P. |editor3-last=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |date=1996 |publisher=IUCN |location=Gland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |page=146}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis yagouarundi'' was the [[scientific name]] used by [[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]] in 1803 who described two [[zoological specimen|specimen]]s from Central America, including one from [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, \u00c9. |authorlink=\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire |year=1803 |title=Catalogue des Mammif\u00e8res du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |trans-title=Catalogue of Mammals of the National Museum of Natural History| language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |page=124 |chapter=Le chat yagouarundi. ''Felis yagouarundi'' (The cat jaguarundi: ''Felis yagouarundi'')|chapter-url={{Google Books|id=951AAAAAcAAJ|page=124|plainurl=yes}} }}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several more specimens, presumably jaguarundis, were described:\n*''Felis eyra'' proposed by [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim]] in 1814 was a [[rust (color)|ferruginous]] skin from [[Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Fischer von Waldheim, G. |authorlink=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim |year=1814 |title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata : in usum praelectionum Academiae imperialis medico-chirugicae mosquensis edita |language=Latin |location=Moscow |publisher=Nicolai S. Vsevolozsky |page=228 |chapter=''Felis eyra'' |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc/page/228}}</ref>\n*[[Gulf Coast Jaguarundi|''F. cacomitli'']] proposed by [[Jean-Louis Berlandier]] in 1859 was a skull and a grayish skin of a female from the [[Rio Grande]] area in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Berlandier, J.-L. |authorlink=Jean-Louis Berlandier |year=1859 |title=Report on the United States and Mexican boundary survey made under the direction of the Secretary of the Interior |volume=II. Mammals of the boundary |editor1=Baird, S. F. |location=Washington |publisher=A.O.P. Nicholson |pages=12\u201313 |chapter=''Felis yagouarundi'' (Desm.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKogAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA12#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi tolteca'' proposed by [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1898 was a skull and a reddish skin from [[Sinaloa]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas |year=1898 |title=On new mammals from Western Mexico and Lower California |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=7 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201346 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof711898lond/page/40}}</ref>\n*''F. ameghinoi'' proposed by [[Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg]] in 1898 for bones, presumably of a jaguarundi, found near [[San Luis, Argentina]], which are embalmed in the [[Turin Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Holmberg, E. L. |authorlink=Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg |year=1898 |chapter=La fauna de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina (The fauna of the Argentine Republic) |pages=477\u2013602 |title=Segundo Censo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina Mayo 10 de 1895 |trans-title=Second Census of the Argentine Republic May 10, 1895 |volume=1 |editor=Carrasco, G. |publisher=Taller Tipogr\u00e1fico de la Penitenciar\u00eda Nacional |location=Buenos Aires }}</ref>\n*''F. fossata'' by [[Edgar Alexander Mearns]] in 1901 was a large skull from [[Yucat\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mearns, E.A. |authorlink=Edgar Alexander Mearns |year=1901 |title=Two new cats of the eyra group from North America |volume=14 |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |pages=149\u2013151 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio14biol/page/148}}</ref>\n*''F. panamensis'' by [[Joel Asaph Allen]] in 1904 was a dusky gray skin of a young adult female collected in Panama's [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J.A. |authorlink=Joel Asaph Allen |year=1904 |title=Mammals from southern Mexico and Central and South America |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=29\u201380 |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/662//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/bul/B020a04.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n*''F. yagouaroundi melantho'' by Oldfield Thomas in 1914 were skulls and blackish brown skins of a male and a female from [[Pozuzo District|Pozuzu]] in Peru.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1914 |title=On various South-American mammals |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=13 |issue=75 |pages=345\u2013363 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof1319unse/page/350}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Genus (biology)|generic]] name ''Herpailurus'' was proposed by [[Nikolai Severtzov]] in 1858 for the jaguarundi.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Severtzow |first1=M. N. |year=1858 |title=Notice sur la classification multis\u00e9riale des Carnivores, sp\u00e9cialement des F\u00e9lid\u00e9s, et les \u00e9tudes de zoologie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale qui s'y rattachent |trans-title=Notes on the classification of the carnivores, especially the Felidae, and the respective zoological studies |journal=Revue et Magasin de Zoologie Pure et Appliqu\u00e9e |volume=X |language=French| pages=385\u2013396 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revueetmagasinde10soci#page/390/mode/2up}}</ref> Later authors classified the jaguarundi in the genus ''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]'' along with the [[cougar]] (''P. concolor'').<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000211 |heading=Species ''Puma yagouaroundi'' |page=545}}</ref>\n[[Phylogeography|Phylogeographical]] analysis of jaguarundi samples from across its range found no genetic evidence for subspecies.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |author2=Pinedo-Castro, M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |pages=245\u2013288 |chapter=Population genetics and phylogeographic analyses of the jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') by means of three mitochondrial markers: The first molecular study of this species |title=Molecular Population Genetics, Evolutionary Biology and Biological Conservation on Neotropical Carnivores |editor1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |editor2=Shostell, J. M. |publisher=Nova Publishers |location=New York |isbn=978-1-62417-079-9 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/230597248_Population_genetics_and_phylogeographic_of_the_jaguarundi_Puma_yaguaroundi_by_means_of_three_mitochondrial_markers_the_first_molecular_population_study_of_this_species_Chapter_8_Molecular_Population_G}}</ref> The jaguarundi is therefore considered to be a [[monotypic taxon]] of the genus ''Herpailurus'' since 2017.<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |display-authors=23 |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n\n==Phylogeny and evolution==\n{{cladogram|title=\n|align=left\n|caption=The ''Puma'' lineage of the family [[Felidae]], depicted along with closely related genera.<ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W.E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae) |year=2010 |pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142 |editor1-last=Macdonald |editor1-first=D.W. |editor2-last=Loveridge |editor2-first=A.J. |title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-19-923445-5 |edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n|1={{clade | style=font-size:90%;line-height:100%;width:450px;\n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |label1=''Lynx'' lineage\n         |1=''[[Lynx (genus)|Lynx]]''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{clade\n            |label1=''Puma'' lineage\n            |1={{clade\n               |label1=''[[Acinonyx]]''\n               |1= ''Acinonyx jubatus'' <br/>([[Cheetah]]) |image1=[[File:Cynailurus guttata - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam - (white background).jpg|80px|left]]\n               |2={{clade\n                  |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n                  |1=''Puma concolor'' <br/>([[Cougar]]) |image1=[[File:Felis concolor - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam -(white background).jpg|70px|left]]\n                  |label2='''''Herpailurus'''''&nbsp;\n                  |2=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' <br/>('''Jaguarundi''')\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=Domestic cat lineage\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''\n            |label2=Leopard cat lineage\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Otocolobus]]''\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n}}\n\nThe jaguarundi is most closely related to the cougar and [[cheetah]].<ref name=\"Culver\">{{cite journal |author1=Culver, M. |author2=Johnson, W. E. |author3=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author4=O'Brien, S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2000 |title=Genomic Ancestry of the American Puma |journal=[[Journal of Heredity]] |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186 |pmid=10833043 |url-status=dead |url=http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616200443/http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> These three species together form the ''Puma'' lineage, one of the eight lineages of Felidae; the ''Puma'' lineage [[Genetic divergence|diverged]] from the rest 6.7 [[Mya (unit)|mya]]. The [[sister group]] of the ''Puma'' lineage is a [[clade]] of smaller [[Old World]] cats that includes the genera ''[[Felis]]'', ''[[Otocolobus]]'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]''.<ref name=\"werdelin\"/> \n\nThe three species of the ''Puma'' lineage may have had a [[common ancestor]] during the [[Miocene]], about {{mya|8.25}}.<ref name=\"adams\">{{cite journal |last1=Adams |first1=D. B. |title=The cheetah: native American |journal=Science |year=1979 |volume=205 |issue=4411 |pages=1155\u20131158 |doi=10.1126/science.205.4411.1155 |pmid=17735054 |bibcode=1979Sci...205.1155A |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6901/86b75e66b681ff0d83772f74068cd1b908b5.pdf}}</ref><ref name=johnson>{{cite journal |pmid=9071018 |year=1997 |last1=Johnson |first1=W. E. |last2=O'Brien |first2=S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Phylogenetic reconstruction of the Felidae using 16S rRNA and NADH-5 mitochondrial genes |volume=44 |issue=S1 |pages=S98\u2013S116 |journal=Journal of Molecular Evolution |doi=10.1007/PL00000060|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232587 |bibcode=1997JMolE..44S..98J}}</ref> ''Acinonyx'' possibly diverged from the lineage in the Americas;<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal |last1=Johnson |first1=W.E. |last2=Eizirik |first2=E. |last3=Pecon-Slattery |first3=J. |last4=Murphy |first4=W.J. |last5=Antunes |first5=A. |last6=Teeling |first6=E. |last7=O'Brien |first7=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |doi=10.1126/science.1122277 |title=The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=311 |pages=73\u201377 |pmid=16400146 |issue=5757 |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1230866}}</ref><ref name=dobrynin>{{cite journal |last1=Dobrynin |first1=P. |last2=Liu |first2=S. |last3=Tamazian |first3 = G. |last4=Xiong |first4=Z. |last5=Yurchenko |first5=A. A. |last6=Krasheninnikova |first6=K. |last7=Kliver |first7=S. |last8=Schmidt-K\u00fcntzel |first8=A. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genomic legacy of the African cheetah, ''Acinonyx jubatus'' |journal=Genome Biology |year=2015 |volume=16 |pages=277 |doi=10.1186/s13059-015-0837-4 |pmid=26653294 |pmc=4676127}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Brien |first1=S. J. |last2=Johnson |first2=W. E. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The evolution of cats |journal=Scientific American |date=2007 |volume=297 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201375 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0707-68 |url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/O%27brien2007EvolutionCats.pdf}}</ref> some authors alternatively suggest that the cheetah diverged in the Old World.<ref>{{cite journal |first=R. |last=Barnett |author2=I. B. |author3=Phillips, M. J. |author4=Martin, L. D. |author5=Harington, C. R. |author6=Leonard, J. A. |author7=Cooper, A. |year=2005 |title=Evolution of the extinct Sabretooths and the American cheetah-like cat |journal=[[Current Biology]] |volume=15 |issue=15 |pages=R589\u2013R590 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2005.07.052 |pmid=16085477}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faurby |first1=S. |last2=Werdelin |first2=L. |last3=Svenning |first3=J. C. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The difference between trivial and scientific names: there were never any true cheetahs in North America |journal=Genome Biology |year=2016 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=89 |doi=10.1186/s13059-016-0943-y|pmid=27150269 |pmc=4858926}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Puma'' lineage appears to have migrated from Asia to North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]], arriving in South America via the [[Isthmus of Panama]] by [[Late Pliocene]] or [[Early Pleistocene]]. This was possibly followed by the bifurcation of the lineage into the cougar and ''Herpailurus'' (represented by ''H. pumoides'') in South America around {{mya|4|3}} between the Late Pliocene and Early Pleistocene. ''H. pumoides'' went extinct around [[Middle Pleistocene]], around the time the modern jaguarundi came into existence; the oldest fossils of the modern jaguarundi date back to the [[Late Pleistocene]] in Brazil around {{mya|0.5}}. The original North American cougars were extripated during the [[Pleistocene extinctions]] around 10,000 years ago; then North America was recolonized by South American cougars and jaguarundis 10,000\u20138,000 years ago.<ref name=bellani/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Culver |first1=M. |title=Genomic ancestry of the American puma (''Puma concolor'') |journal=Journal of Heredity |date=2000 |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chimento |first1=N.R. |last2=Dondas |first2=A. |title=First record of ''Puma concolor'' (Mammalia, Felidae) in the Early-Middle Pleistocene of South America |journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution |date=2017 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=381\u2013389 |doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9385-x}}</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header    = \n| header_align = center\n\n| image1    = Jaguarondi 2.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = <center>Red morph</center>\n\n| image2    = Jaguarundi seitlich.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  = <center>Gray morph</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}} \nThe jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats in its external appearance. This has been attributed to variations in its [[karyotype]]\u2014the jaguarundi has 38 [[chromosome]]s, unlike the 36 in other small South American cats, and the chromosomal features resemble those of Old World cats such as the [[leopard cat]] (''Prionailurus bengalensis'').<ref name=WCoW/> Interestingly, the jaguarundi is characterized by several [[mustelid]] features\u2014an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. As such, the jaguarundi is sometimes considered similar to [[marten]]s, [[otter]]s or [[weasel]]s.<ref name=\"bellani\">{{cite book |last1=Bellani |first1=G.G. |title=Felines of the World: Discoveries in Taxonomic Classification and History |date=2020 |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-12-816503-4 |pages=223-231 |url={{Google Books|id=xK2wDwAAQBAJ|page=223|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|page=818|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=818|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The head-and-body length is between {{convert|53|and|77|cm|in|abbr=on}}; the strong, muscular tail is {{convert|31|\u2013|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. Around twice as large as the [[domestic cat]], the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though larger individuals weighing around {{convert|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}} have been reported.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |author1=Sunquist, M. |author2=Sunquist, F. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild Cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |pages=113\u2013119 |isbn= 978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/113}}</ref><ref name=\"fws.gov\">{{Cite journal |author1=Brown, D.E. |author2=Gonzalez, C.A. |year=1999 |title=Jaguarundi (''Felis yagouaroundi tolteca'') |url=http://www.fws.gov/southwest/es/Arizona/Documents/Redbook/Jaguarundi%20RB.pdf |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |issue=32 |pages=155\u2013157}}</ref> Males are slightly larger than females.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nThe coat is uniformly colored with at most a few faint markings on the face and the belly, though kittens may be spotted for a short duration. Black and white marks on the lips and the snout, similar to those of the cougar, can be clearly seen in juveniles and some adults. The fur color varies from blackish to brownish-grey with a grizzled look due to alternating bright and dark rings on individual hairs (called gray [[Morph (biology)|morph]]), to foxy red to chestnut (called red morph); earlier these morphs were considered two different species. Individuals of both colors can be born in the same litter.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=\"hildyard\">{{cite book |last1=Sirimarco |first1=E. |editor1-last=Hildyard |editor1-first=A. |title=Endangered Wildlife and Plants of the World (Volume 6) |date=2001 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Co |location=New York |isbn=0-7614-7200-2 |pages=736-738 |chapterurl={{Google Books|plainurl=yes|id=5YYqd4ROFfkC|page=736}} |chapter=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yaguarondi cacomitli'')}}</ref> Blackish brown individuals superficially resemble the [[tayra]] (''Eira barbara''), but the latter can be told apart by the clear, yellowish patch on the throat.<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite journal |last1=de Oliveira |first1=T.G. |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |journal=Mammalian Species |date=1998 |issue=578 |pages=1-6 |doi=10.2307/3504500 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275737351_Herpailurus_yagouaroundi}}</ref> The red morph is seen more often in dry, open areas. [[Melanism|melanistic]] individuals have been reported, but they are not completely black; the head and the throat are clearly paler than the rest of the body.<ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=152\u2013156|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=152|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref>  The ears, {{convert|2.5|\u2013|4|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, are widely spaced and, unlike many other felids, lack white spots on the back.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos>{{cite book |author1-last=Aranda |author1-first=M. |author2-last=Caso |author2-first=A. |editor1-last=Ceballos |editor1-first=G. |title=Mammals of Mexico |publisher=John Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-1-4214-0879-8 |pages=498-499 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl={{Google Books|page=498|plainurl=yes|id=UrvxBQAAQBAJ}}}}</ref> The jaguarundi has a total of 30 teeth; the [[dental formula]] is {{DentalFormula|upper=3.1.3.1|lower=3.1.2.1}}.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nAmong felids, the jaguarundi is closely similar to the [[flat-headed cat]] (''Prionailurus planiceps''), but has a longer body and proportionately longer legs, is heavier and lacks the dark markings on the cheeks of the flat-headed cat.<ref name=ms/> Tawny jaguarundis bear a similar coloration as the signficantly larger cougar.<ref name=Hunter/>\n\n==Behavior and ecology==\n[[File:Jaguarondi 1.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are good climbers and can easily walk on branches.]]\nThe jaguarundi is shy and reclusive, and apparently very cautious of [[Animal trapping|traps]].<ref name=Simberloff/> There have been only a few [[radio telemetry]] studies of jaguarundis in Belize, Brazil and Mexico.<ref name=Hunter/> Though activity has been observed throughout the day and at night, jaguarundis seem to prefer hunting during daytime and evening hours; a study in Belize reported that jaguarundis started moving before dawn and remained active through most of the day till sunset with a peak in hunting from late morning to noon.<ref name=ms/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Konecny |first1=M.J. |title=Movement patterns and food habits of four sympatric carnivore species in Belize, South America |journal=Advances in Neotropical Mammalogy |date=1989 |pages=243-264 |url=http://library.bfreebz.org/Mammals/Michael%20Konecny,%20Movement%20Patterns%20and%20Food%20Habits%20of%20Four%20Sympatric%20Carnivore%20Species%20in%20Belize,%20Central%20America,%201989.pdf}}</ref> The cat appears to be more [[Diurnality|diurnal]] than most other cats, especially spotted cats that tend to be more active at night.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=WCoW/> The jaguarundi can swim across medium-sized rivers; an individual was recorded swimming across the [[Tuichi River]] (Bolivia).<ref name=Hunter/> Jaguarundis are efficient climbers as well, but hunt mainly on ground; its coat color works as a good camouflage for terrestrial activity.<ref name=Nowak/> They can leap up to {{convert|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} into the air to catch birds.<ref name=WCoW/> Predators recorded for jaguarundis include [[boa constrictor]]s, cougars and [[domestic dog]]s.<ref name=Hunter/> Parasites such as [[hookworm]]s (''[[Ancylostoma]]'' species), [[tapeworm]]s (such as  ''[[Spirometra]]'' and ''[[Toxocara]]'' species) and the [[lung fluke]] have been found in jaguarundis.<ref name=ms/>\n\nStudies have mostly observed jaguarundis alone or in pairs; pairs could probably be formed between mothers and older kittens or between individuals of opposite sexes during the mating season. Individuals in captivity have been found to be more gregarious.<ref name=WCoW/> [[Home range]]s tend to be large; a study in Brazil recorded home ranges {{convert|1.4|\u2013|18|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size for females, while those of males measured {{convert|8.5|\u2013|25.3|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in area.<ref name=Hunter/> Two males in Belize were recorded to have exceptionally large home ranges spanning an area of {{convert|88|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} and {{convert|100|sqkm|sqmi}}, while the home range of a female in the same region measured {{convert|13|\u2013|20|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} in size.<ref name=Nowak/> Population densities are typically low, around {{convert|0.01|to|0.05|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}, though the Llanos in Costa Rica and Venezuela have recorded figures as high as {{convert|0.2|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=bellani/>\n\nMarking behavior could serve as a means of olfactory or visual communication; individuals in captivity have been observed scraping areas with their hind feet (sometimes with urination), clawing on logs, rubbing objects with their heads and leaving feces uncovered. Social behavior such as grooming, growling and sniffing has been recorded. The jaguarundi has a broad vocal repertoire; 13 different calls have been recorded including chattering, purring, screaming, a 'wah-wah' call, whistling, yapping and a peculiar bird-like chirp. In captivity, females in [[estrus]] have been observed making faint sounds as they [[scent mark]] the area around their enclosures.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/> \n\n===Diet===\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi, ZOO Praha 254.jpg|thumb|Jaguarundis are [[Generalist and specialist species|generalist]] carnivores.]]\nThe jaguarundi typically feed on small-sized prey weighing less than {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, including ground-feeding birds, reptiles, [[rodent]]s and small mammals. Jaguarundis will also take larger prey such as domestic poultry, fish, [[marmoset]]s, rabbits and [[opossum]]s; a study recorded small deer (possibly [[carrion]]) in the diet. Vegetation such as grasses have also been recorded in their diet.<ref name=Hunter/><ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/><ref name=ms/> A study showed jaguarundis take {{convert|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} vertebrate prey on an average everyday.<ref name=ms/> The broad array of prey recorded for the jaguarundi across its range and varying proportions of different prey in its diet could indicate that the cat tends to feed on the most abundant and easily catchable prey in the area.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nJaguarundis have been observed mating all year round, with peaks at different times of the year across the range; for instance, in Mexico breeding peaks in January and March. Estrus lasts three to five days, marked by the female regularly rolling onto her back and [[spraying urine]]. [[Sexually mature]] males will pursue the female, not reacting to any aggressive behavior from her side. As in many other felids, the male bites the fur on the female's neck on mounting; the female lets out a loud scream on penetration.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ms/>\n\nAfter a [[gestation]] period of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens in a den constructed in a dense thicket, hollow tree, or similar cover. The kittens are covered well with fur and the underside is marked with spots, which disappear as they age; the coat color gradually changes as the kittens grow older.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos/> The mother starts bringing solid food for the kittens when they are around three weeks old, who simply play with it till the mother ingests it; kittens are capable of taking solid food like birds and guinea pigs at around six weeks. Jaguarundis become sexually mature at one to three years of age. Lifespan up to 15 years has been recorded in captivity.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=Nowak/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe jaguarundi inhabits a wide variety of habitats\u2014from tropical rainforests and [[deciduous forest]]s to deserts and [[thorn scrub]]s. It can also occur in [[cloud forest]]s, [[mangrove]]s and [[savanna]]s.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=ceballos/> Unlike the [[Sympatry|sympatric]] [[margay]], [[ocelot]] and [[oncilla]], the jaguarundi can occur in open areas as well. In open habitats the jaguarundi prefers areas with vegetative cover such as cacti, which would generally be difficult for possible predators to penetrate; there may be a few clearings at the periphery of such areas. Jaguarundis tend to stay close to a source of running water.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=fws.gov/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Coronado-Quibrera |first1=W.P. |last2=Olmos-Oropeza |first2=G. |last3=Bender |first3=L.C. |last4=Rosas-Rosas |first4=O.C. |last5=Palacio-N\u00fa\u00f1ez |first5=J. |last6=Tarango-Ar\u00e1mbula |first6=L.A. |last7=Herrera-Haro |first7=J.G. |title=Adaptability of the threatened jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Schereber, 1777) to human-altered environments in San Luis Potos\u00ed, Mexico |journal=Acta Zool\u00f3gica Mexicana |date=2019 |volume=35 |pages=1\u201315 |doi=10.21829/azm.2019.3502210 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/310f/6597fd914eb664e160637b4b1b1d57d87fe7.pdf}}</ref> The jaguarundi is noted for its resistance to environmental disturbances in its habitat; it can successfully thrive in reforested areas.<ref name=ceballos/> While commonly inhabiting lowlands up to {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the sea level, this cat has been reported at elevations as high as {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Colombia.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThe range extends from central Argentina in the south to the US-Mexico border in the north, through Central and South America east of the Andes\u2014second only to the cougar in the [[Latitude|latitudinal]] extent of its distribution. However, not all parts of its range have been studied well. The jaguarundi is fairly common in Brazil, Peru and Venezuela.<ref name=\"rev\">{{cite journal |last1=Giordano |first1=A.J. |title=Ecology and status of the jaguarundi ''Puma yagouaroundi'': a synthesis of existing knowledge |journal=Mammal Review |date=2016 |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201343 |doi=10.1111/mam.12051 |url=https://carnivores.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Giordano_2015_mam12051_Jaguarundi.pdf}}</ref> It is possibly [[extinct]] in the US;<ref name=iucn/> a study in 1999 refuted claims of sightings in Arizona.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=D.E. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez |first2=C.A.L. |title=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' Geoffroy 1803) not in Arizona or Sonora |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |date=1999 |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=155-157 |jstor=40021308}}</ref> The last confirmed sighting in the US was probably of a roadkilled individual near [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] (Texas) in 1986.<ref name=rev/>\n\nJaguarundis have been sighted in [[Florida]] since the early 20th century; their presence there is attributed to a writer from [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]] who at some point imported the animals from their native habitat and released them near his hometown and in other locations across the state. Several sightings have been reported since 1907; in 1977 [[W. T. Neill]] noted that the population was declining. Jaguarundis have also been reported in the coastal area of [[Alabama]] since the 1980s, which may be evidence of the Florida population migrating northward.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title=Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida |last1=Simberloff |first1=D. |authorlink=Daniel Simberloff |author2=Schmitz, D.C. |author3=Brown, T.C. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1997 |publisher=Island Press |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-55963-430-4 |url={{Google Books |plainurl=yes|page=172|id=rtrpSllq4SQC}} |pages=172\u2013173}}</ref> The jaguarundi has also been recorded from [[Cerro Largo Department|Cerro Largo]] in [[Uruguay]], where its presence was doubted.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Grattarola, F. |author2=Hernandez, D. |author3=Duarte, A. |author4=Gaucher, L. |author5=Perazza, G. |display-authors=3 |year=2016 |title=Primer registro de yaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) en Uruguay, con comentarios sobre monitereo participativo |journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Zool\u00f3gica del Uruguay |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=85\u221291 |language=Spanish |trans-title=First record of jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) in Uruguay, with comments on participatory monitoring}}</ref>\n\n==Threats and conservation==\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi.jpg|thumb|left|Captive jaguarundi in the Zoo de Pont-Scorff (France)]]\nThe jaguarundi has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2002. Mexican populations, except those in the northeast, appear to be stable. The huge reserves of the [[Amazon Basin]] are probably the only conservation units that can sustain long-term viable populations. In its 2015 revision, the IUCN noted that the species should be listed as [[Near Threatened]], but there was not enough data to go upon to extend this classification throughout the range.<ref name=iucn/> The jaguarundi is not particularly sought after for its fur due to its poor quality and low value, but is suffering decline due to habitat loss.<ref name=Nowak/><ref name=fws.gov/> Other threats include risks of [[habitat fragmentation]] and persecution for killing poultry.<ref name=iucn/> The North and Central American populations of the jaguarundi are listed in [[CITES Appendix I]] and all the other populations are listed in [[CITES Appendix II]].<ref name=ceballos/> Populations in the US are protected under the [[Endangered Species Act]];<ref name=MSW3/> the [[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]] has expressed concern that its presence in South Texas may be imperiled due to loss of the cat's native habitat.<ref name=Texas2003>{{cite web |url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/landwater/land/habitats/southtx_plain/endangered_species/ |title=Endangered Species |website=Tpwd.state.tx.us |date=2003-04-15 |access-date=2011-09-15 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Populations in Mexico are listed under the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lorenzo |first1=C. |last2=Gonz\u00e1lez-Ruiz |first2=N. |title=Mammals in the Mexican Official Norm NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010 |journal=Therya |date=2018 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=69\u201372 |doi=10.12933/therya-18-565 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323250093_Mammals_in_the_Mexican_Official_Norm_NOM-059-SEMARNAT-2010}}</ref> Hunting jaguarundi is restricted in Peru and banned in Argentina, Belize, Brazil, Bolivia, Colombia, Costa Rica, French Guiana, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Panama, Paraguay, Suriname, Uruguay, the US and Venezuela.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Acinonychini]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons and category|Puma yagouaroundi|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=93 |title=Jaguarundi ''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |website=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group}}\n* {{cite web |website=Big Cats Online |url=http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031107150747/http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-date=2003-11-07 |df=dmy-all |title=Jaguarundi |series=Wild Cat Species and Distribution \u2013 South America}}\n* {{cite Americana |wstitle=Jaguarondi |short=x}}\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q182304}}\n\n[[Category:Puma (genus)]]\n[[Category:Felids of Central America]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Felids of South America]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Belize]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of French Guiana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Honduras]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Suriname]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Panama]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Peru]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Fauna of northern South America]]\