bums chart for October 12, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|October 19}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-10-19/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for October 19, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|October 26}}\n| ''[[Frame by Frame (album)|Frame by Frame]]''\n| {{sortname|Cassadee|Pope}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-10-26/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for October 26, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 17, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|November 2}}\n| ''[[See You Tonight]]''\n| {{sortname|Scotty|McCreery}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-11-02/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for November 2, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|November 9}}\n| ''[[Crash My Party]]''\n| {{sortname|Luke|Bryan}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-11-09/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for November 9, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|November 16}}\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''[[Duck The Halls: A Robertson Family Christmas]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\"| {{sort|Robertsons|[[Duck Dynasty|The Robertsons]]}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-11-16/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for November 16, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|November 23}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-11-23/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for November 23, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|November 30}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-11-30/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for November 30, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|December 7}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-12-07/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for December 7, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 28, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|December 14}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''[[Blame It All on My Roots: Five Decades of Influences]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| {{sortname|Garth|Brooks}}\n| align=center|<ref name=GB>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-12-14/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for December 14, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|December 21}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-12-21/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for December 21, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|December 28}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-12-28/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for December 28, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2013 in music]]\n*[[List of number-one country singles of 2013 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{US Country Albums}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of number-one country albums in the United States|2013]]\n[[Category:2013 record charts|United States Country Albums]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Cheyenne Frontier Days (28690466397).jpg|thumb|right|250px|alt=The band Florida Georgia Line|''[[Here's to the Good Times]]'', the debut album by [[Florida Georgia Line]], spent eight weeks at number one.]]\n[[Top Country Albums]] is a [[record chart|chart]] that ranks the top-performing [[country music]] albums in the United States, published by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.  In 2013, 21 different albums topped the chart; placings were based on electronic [[point of sale]] data from retail outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7669133/billboard-genre-album-charts-consumption-streams-track-sales|title=Billboard's Genre Album Charts Will Now Incorporate Streams & Track Sales|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the issue of ''Billboard'' dated January 5, [[Taylor Swift]] was at number one with ''[[Red (Taylor Swift album)|Red]]'', the album's ninth week at number one.<ref name=J7 />  The album spent eight weeks in the top spot in 2013, but would prove to be Swift's last entry on the Top Country Albums chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/taylor-swift/chart-history/CLP|title=Taylor Swift Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> as she moved away from the country music genre with her subsequent releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/taylor-swift-mn0000472102/biography|title=Taylor Swift Biographty & History|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>  With eight weeks atop the chart, ''Red'' tied with ''[[Here's to the Good Times]]'', the debut album by [[Florida Georgia Line]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/a31926713/florida-georgia-line-new-song-album-i-love-my-country-interview/|title=It's Time to Rethink Florida Georgia Line, One of Country's Biggest Shapeshifters|work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|first=Madison|last=Vain|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> for the most time spent at number one in 2013 by an album.  [[Luke Bryan]], the only artist with more than one number one in 2013, had the highest total number of weeks at number one by an artist during the year: he spent two weeks in the peak position with ''[[Spring Break\u2026Here to Party]]'' and seven with ''[[Crash My Party]]''.  Both Bryan and Florida Georgia Line were associated with the so-called [[bro-country]] style, an emerging sub-genre which incorporated influences from [[rock music]] and [[hip hop music|hip hop]] and often featured lyrics relating to partying, attractive young women, and pick-up trucks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/the-appeal-and-possible-end-of-beer-drinking-hip-shaking-woman-ogling-bro-country|title=The New Country|work=[[National Post]]|first=Sarah|last=Boesveld|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=So Long Bro: Chase Rice Rejects Bro-Country Past With New Label + Album|url=https://tasteofcountry.com/chase-rice-rejects-bro-country-new-album-lambs-and-lions-broken-bow/|first=Laura|last=McClellan|date=July 1, 2017|accessdate=April 15, 2020|work=Taste of Country|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Florida Georgia Line, several other acts reached number one for the first time in 2013.  In April, [[Kacey Musgraves]] and [[The Band Perry]] both gained their first chart-toppers with ''[[Same Trailer Different Park]]'' and ''[[Pioneer (The Band Perry album)|Pioneer]]'' respectively,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/monicamercuri/2019/02/20/kacey-musgraves-reclaims-top-country-albums-no-1-following-grammy-success|title=Kacey Musgraves Reclaims Top Country Albums No. 1 Following Grammy Success|work=[[Forbes]]|first=Monica|last=Mercuri|date=February 20, 2019|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/1557266/band-perry-notches-first-no-1-on-top-country-albums-chart|title=Band Perry Notches First No. 1 On Top Country Albums Chart|first=Wade|last=Jessen|date=April 11, 2013|accessdate=April 16, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>  and [[Hunter Hayes]] achieved the same feat in July with his [[Hunter Hayes (album)|eponymous album]].  Hayes's album reached the top spot in its 89th week on the chart, the longest time taken for an album to reach number one since ''Billboard'' began using electronic sales data in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1568556/hunter-hayes-completes-record-run-to-no-1-on-top-country-albums|title=Hunter Hayes Completes Record Run To No. 1 On Top Country Albums|first=Wade|last=Jessen|date=June 27, 2013|accessdate=April 16, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>  [[Cassadee Pope]], the winner of the [[The Voice (American season 3)|third season]] of TV singing contest ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' late the previous year,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/04/23/winning-voice-changed-cassadee-popes-life-her-career-is-still-evolving/|title=Winning \u2018The Voice\u2019 changed Cassadee Pope\u2019s life. Six years later, her career is still evolving.|work=[[Washington Post]]|first=Emily|last=Yahr|date=April 23, 2019|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> gained her first number one album in October with ''[[Frame by Frame (album)|Frame by Frame]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cassadee-pope/chart-history/CLP|title=Cassadee Pope Chart History|accessdate=April 16, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]</ref>  In December, the Robertson family from the TV show ''[[Duck Dynasty]]'' topped the chart with their debut album ''[[Duck The Halls: A Robertson Family Christmas]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5770556/duck-dynasty-family-releasing-a-christmas-album|title='Duck Dynasty' Family Releasing a Christmas Album|first=Kevin|last=Rutherford|date=October 25, 2013|accessdate=April 16, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>  It was displaced in the issue of ''Billboard'' dated December 14 by the compilation album ''[[Blame It All on My Roots: Five Decades of Influences]]'' by [[Garth Brooks]], which entered the chart at number one.<ref name=GB />  Brooks's compilation was one of several of 2013's Top Country Albums number ones to also top the all-genre [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, along with albums by Taylor Swift, [[Gary Allan]], Luke Bryan, [[Kenny Chesney]], [[Lady Antebellum]] and [[Keith Urban]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316065515/https://www.billboard.com/archive/charts/2013/billboard-200|title=Billboard 200 - 2013 Archive|accessdate=April 16, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n[[File:Begin Again (9492115952) (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Taylor Swift|[[Taylor Swift]] spent eight weeks at number one with the album ''[[Red (Taylor Swift album)|Red]]''.]]\n[[File:Willie Robertson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=TV personality Willie Robertson|The Robertson family from the TV show ''[[Duck Dynasty]]'' ([[Willie Robertson]] pictured) topped the chart with ''[[Duck The Halls: A Robertson Family Christmas]]''.]]\n[[File:Hunter Hayes, Koko, London (17381085323).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Hunter Hayes|[[Hunter Hayes]] reached number one for the first time with his [[Hunter Hayes (album)|eponymous album]].]]\n[[File:Cassadee Pope in 2019.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Cassadee Pope|[[Cassadee Pope]], the winner of the [[The Voice (American season 3)|third season]] of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'', topped the chart with her debut album.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=col|Issue date\n!scope=col|Title\n!scope=col|Artist(s)\n!scope=col class=unsortable|Ref.\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|January 5}}\n| rowspan=\"5\"| ''[[Red (Taylor Swift album)|Red]]''\n| rowspan=\"5\"| {{sortname|Taylor|Swift}}\n| align=center|<ref name=J7>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-01-05/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for January 5, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 27, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|January 12}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-01-12/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for January 12, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|January 19}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-01-19/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for January 19, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 10, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|January 26}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-01-26/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for January 26, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 17, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|February 2}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-02-02/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for February 2, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|February 9}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Set You Free (Gary Allan album)|Set You Free]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{sortname|Gary|Allan}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-02-09/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for February 9, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|February 16}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-02-16/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for February 16, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|February 23}}\n| ''[[Two Lanes of Freedom]]''\n| {{sortname|Tim|McGraw}}\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-02-23/country-albums|title=Country Albums chart for February 23, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 14, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|March 2